ns]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Loire-Atlantique|44]]||[[La Baule-les-Pins]]\n|[[TER Pays de la Loire]]\n|- \n| style=\"background:#0080c0;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">o</span>||[[gare de La Baule-Escoublac|'''La Baule-Escoublac''']]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Loire-Atlantique|44]]||[[La Baule-Escoublac]]||[[TGV]], [[Intercit\u00e9s]], [[TER Pays de la Loire]]\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n| style=\"background:#0080c0;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">o</span>||[[gare du Pouliguen|'''Le Pouliguen''']]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Loire-Atlantique|44]]||[[Le Pouliguen]]||[[TER Pays de la Loire]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#0080c0;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">o</span>||'''[[Gare de Batz-sur-Mer|Batz-sur-Mer]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Loire-Atlantique|44]]||[[Batz-sur-Mer]]\n|[[TER Pays de la Loire]]\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n| style=\"background:#0080c0;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">o</span>||[[gare du Croisic|'''Le Croisic''']]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Loire-Atlantique|44]]||[[Le Croisic]]||[[TGV]], [[Intercit\u00e9s]], [[TER Pays de la Loire]]\n|}\n\n<br />\n\n[[Category:Transport in Centre-Val de Loire]]\n[[Category:Transport express r\u00e9gional]]\n\n\n{{France-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Epluribusunumyall", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoute", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interloire"}
{"title_page": "Johann Kupferburger", "text_new": "{{short description|South African tennis player}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n | name = Johann Kupferburger\n | image =  \n | caption =\n | country = {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[South Africa]]\n | residence = \n | birth_date = 10 February 1933\n | birth_place = [[Pretoria]], South Africa\n | death_date =  December 1988\n | death_place = [[Johannesburg]], South Africa\n | height = \n | turnedpro = 1951<small>(amateur tour)</small>\n | retired = 1958\n | plays =\n | careerprizemoney = \n | singlesrecord = 91\u201361<small>(4\u20136 per ATP)</small>\n | singlestitles = 3\n | highestsinglesranking = \n | AustralianOpenresult = \n | FrenchOpenresult = 2R ([[1953 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1953]])\n | Wimbledonresult = 1R ([[1951 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1951]], [[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1953]])\n | USOpenresult = 3R ([[1955 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1955]])\n | doublesrecord = \n | doublestitles = \n | highestdoublesranking = \n | AustralianOpenDoublesresult = \n | FrenchOpenDoublesresult = \n | WimbledonDoublesresult = 2R ([[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Doubles|1953]])\n | USOpenDoublesresult = \n | Mixed = yes\n | mixedtitles = \n | mixedrecord = \n | AustralianOpenMixedresult = \n | FrenchOpenMixedresult = \n | WimbledonMixedresult = 4R ([[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Mixed Doubles|1953]])\n | USOpenMixedresult =\n}}\n\n''' Johann Friedrich Kupferburger''' (10 February 1933 \u2013 December 1988) was a South African tennis player who was active in the 1950s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/players/johann-kupferburger/kf76/overview|title=Johann Kupferburger{{!}} Player Stats {{!}} ATP Tour {{!}} Tennis|website=ATP Tour|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=South African Families Vol 20|publisher=Genealogical Institute of South Africa|year=2015|isbn=|location=Stellenbosch|pages=768}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nKupferburger won the [[1951 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Boys' Singles|1951 Wimbledon Boys' Singles]] title by beating the Egyptian player, Kamel Moubarek in the final. He attended college in the United States at the [[University of Miami]], where he was a member of the university's tennis team and he earned All-American honours in 1957.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itatennis.com/ITA/Awards/All-America_Teams/ITA/Awards/All-America_Teams.aspx?hkey=9ff2d40b-5c92-456a-afb7-150688a60f14|title=All-America Teams|website=www.itatennis.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\nKupferburger also competed on the amateur circuit and won 3 titles. His first title was in August 1955 when he won the Ontario Championships, beating [[Gardnar Mulloy]] in the final. The next week he was successful again when he won the Cleveland House Invitation by defeating Gilbert Bogley in the final. His last title was almost three years later, at the 1958 Oakville Invitation, beating the Canadian [[Donald Fontana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennisarchives.com/player/?pl=3811|title=player \u2013 Tennisarchives.com|website=www.tennisarchives.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nHis best result at a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] events was reaching the third round at the [[1955 U.S. National Championships (tennis) |1955 US Open]], before losing to [[Art Larsen]]. After retiring as player he worked as a tennis coach in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/players/johann-kupferburger/kf76/overview|title=Johann Kupferburger {{!}} Player Activity {{!}} ATP Tour {{!}} Tennis|website=ATP Tour|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Junior Grand Slam titles==\n===Singles: 1===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=font-size:97%\n|-\n!Result\n!Year\n!width=150|Tournament\n!Surface\n!width=150|Opponent\n!width=150|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| [[1951 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Boys' Singles|1951]]\n| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n| [[Grass court|Grass]]\n| {{flagicon|EGY|1922}} Kamel Moubarek\n| 6\u20132, 6\u20131\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links== \n* {{ATP|id= kf76}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kupferburger, Johann}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:South African male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African tennis player}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n | name = Johann Kupferburger\n | image =  \n | caption =\n | country = {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[South Africa]]\n | residence = \n | birth_date = 10 February 1933\n | birth_place = [[Pretoria]], South Africa\n | death_date =  December 1988\n | death_place = [[Johannesburg]], South Africa\n | height = \n | turnedpro = 1951<small>(amateur tour)</small>\n | retired = 1958\n | plays =\n | careerprizemoney = \n | singlesrecord = 91\u201361<small>(4\u20136 per ATP)</small>\n | singlestitles = 3\n | highestsinglesranking = \n | AustralianOpenresult = \n | FrenchOpenresult = 2R ([[1953 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1953]])\n | Wimbledonresult = 1R ([[1951 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1951]], [[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1953]])\n | USOpenresult = 3R ([[1955 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1955]])\n | doublesrecord = \n | doublestitles = \n | highestdoublesranking = \n | AustralianOpenDoublesresult = \n | FrenchOpenDoublesresult = \n | WimbledonDoublesresult = 2R ([[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Doubles|1953]])\n | USOpenDoublesresult = \n | Mixed = yes\n | mixedtitles = \n | mixedrecord = \n | AustralianOpenMixedresult = \n | FrenchOpenMixedresult = \n | WimbledonMixedresult = 4R ([[1953 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Mixed Doubles|1953]])\n | USOpenMixedresult =\n}}\n\n''' Johann Friedrich Kupferburger''' (10 February 1933 \u2013 December 1988) was a South African tennis player who was active in the 1950s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/players/johann-kupferburger/kf76/overview|title=Johann Kupferburger{{!}} Player Stats {{!}} ATP Tour {{!}} Tennis|website=ATP Tour|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=South African Families Vol 20|publisher=Genealogical Institute of South Africa|year=2015|isbn=|location=Stellenbosch|pages=768}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nKupferburger won the [[1951 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Boys' Singles|1951 Wimbledon Boys' Singles]] title by beating the Egyptian player, Kamel Moubarek in the final. He attended college in the United States at the [[University of Miami]], where he was a member of the university's tennis team and he earned All-American honours in 1957.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itatennis.com/ITA/Awards/All-America_Teams/ITA/Awards/All-America_Teams.aspx?hkey=9ff2d40b-5c92-456a-afb7-150688a60f14|title=All-America Teams|website=www.itatennis.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\nKupferburger also competed on the amateur circuit and won 3 titles. His first title was in August 1955 when he won the Ontario Championships, beating [[Gardnar Mulloy]] in the final. The next week he was successful again when he won the Cleveland House Invitation by defeating Gilbert Bogley in the final. His last title was almost three years later, at the 1958 Oakville Invitation, beating the Canadian [[Donald Fontana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennisarchives.com/player/?pl=3811|title=player \u2013 Tennisarchives.com|website=www.tennisarchives.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nHis best result at a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] events was reaching the third round at the [[1955 U.S. National Championships (tennis) |1955 US Open]], before losing to [[Art Larsen]]. After retiring as player he worked as a tennis coach in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/players/johann-kupferburger/kf76/overview|title=Johann Kupferburger {{!}} Player Activity {{!}} ATP Tour {{!}} Tennis|website=ATP Tour|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Junior Grand Slam titles==\n===Singles: 1===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=font-size:97%\n|-\n!Result\n!Year\n!width=150|Tournament\n!Surface\n!width=150|Opponent\n!width=150|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| [[1951 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Boys' Singles|1951]]\n| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n| [[Grass court|Grass]]\n| {{flagicon|EGY|1922}} Kamel Moubarek\n| 6\u20132, 6\u20131\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links== \n* {{ATP|id= kf76}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kupferburger, Johann}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category: South African male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n", "name_user": "Tamolyn", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johann_Kupferburger"}
{"title_page": "Texture (music)", "text_new": "{{short description|Way in which tempo, melody, and harmony are combined in a musical composition}}\n{{Use Harvard referencing|date=December 2019}}\n[[Image:Sousa - \"Washington Post March,\" m. 1-7.png|thumb|300px|Introduction to [[John Philip Sousa|Sousa]]'s \"[[The Washington Post (march)|Washington Post March]],\" mm. 1\u20137{{audio|Sousa - \"Washington Post March,\" m. 1-7.mid|Play}} features [[octave doubling]] {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=133}} and a homorhythmic texture.]]smd mother fer\n\nIn [[music]], '''texture''' is how the [[tempo]], [[melody|melodic]], and [[harmony|harmonic]] materials are combined in a [[musical composition|composition]], thus determining the overall quality of the sound in a piece. Texture is often described in regard to the density, or thickness, and [[range (music)|range]], or width, between lowest and highest pitches, in relative terms as well as more specifically distinguished according to the number of voices, or parts, and the relationship between these voices (see [[#Common types|Common types]] below). For example, a thick texture contains many 'layers' of instruments. One of these layers could be a string section, or another brass. The thickness also is changed by the amount and the richness of the instruments playing the piece. The thickness varies from light to thick. A piece's texture may be changed by the number and character of parts playing at once, the [[timbre]] of the instruments or voices playing these parts and the harmony, [[tempo]], and rhythms used {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|loc={{Page needed|date=August 2015}}}}. The types categorized by number and relationship of parts are analyzed and determined through the labeling of primary textural elements: primary melody (PM), secondary melody (SM), parallel supporting melody (PSM), static support (SS), harmonic support (HS), rhythmic support (RS), and harmonic and rhythmic support (HRS) {{harv|Isaac & Russell|2003|p=136}}.\n\n==Common types==\nIn musical terms, particularly in the fields of music history and music analysis, some common terms for different types of texture are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Type\n! Description\n! Visual\n! Audio\n|-\n| [[Monophony|Monophonic]]\n| Monophonic texture includes a single melodic line with no accompaniment. {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=136}}. PSMs often double or parallel the PM they support {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n| [[Image:Pop Goes the Weasel melody.PNG|thumb|250px|\"[[Pop Goes the Weasel]]\" melody {{harv|Kliewer|1975|pp=270\u2013301}}.]]\n| {{Listen|filename=Pop Goes the Weasel.ogg|title=Pop Goes the Weasel|image=none|description=Tune for ''Pop Goes the Weasel''}}\n|-\n| Biphonic\n| Two distinct lines, the lower sustaining a drone (constant pitch) while the other line creates a more elaborate melody above it. [[Pedal point|Pedal tone]]s or [[ostinati]] would be an example of a SS {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n| [[Image:Pedal tone Bach - BWV 851, m.1-2.png|thumb|250px|Pedal tone in Bach's Prelude no. 6 in D Minor, BWV 851, from ''The Well Tempered Clavier'', Book I, mm.&nbsp;1\u20132. All pedal tone notes are consonant except for the last three of the first measure {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=99}}.]]\n| {{Listen|filename=Pedal tone Bach - BWV 851, m.1-2.mid|title=Pedal tone Bach|image=none|description=Pedal tone in Bach's Prelude no. 6 in D Minor, BWV 851, from ''The Well Tempered Clavier'', Book I, mm.&nbsp;1\u20132.}}\n|-\n|[[Polyphony|Polyphonic]] or [[Counterpoint]] or [[Contrapuntal]]\n| Multiple melodic voices which are to a considerable extent independent from or in imitation with one another. Characteristic texture of the [[Renaissance music]], also prevalent during the [[Baroque music|Baroque period]] {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|pp=1999,199,158,137, 136,129,110,90,59,35,11,9,0){{Verify source|date=August 2015}}<!--What is this, vandalism?-->}}. Polyphonic textures may contain several PMs {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n|[[File:BachFugueBar.png|thumb|right|250px|A bar from [[J.S. Bach]]'s \"[[Fugue]] No.17 in A flat\", BWV 862, from ''[[Well-tempered Clavier|Das Wohltemperirte Clavier]]'' (Part I), a famous example of '''[[counterpoint|contrapuntal polyphony]]'''. {{audio|BachFugueBar.mid|Play}}]]\n|{{Listen|filename=Johann Sebastian Bach - The Well-tempered Clavier - Book 1 - 11Efuge Bbmaj.ogg|image=none|title= Book 1 \u2013 Fugue No. 21 in B-flat major (BWV 866)|description=performed on a Flemish harpsichord by Martha Goldstein|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n|-\n|[[Homophony|Homophonic]]\n|The most common texture in Western music: melody and accompaniment. Multiple voices of which one, the melody, stands out prominently and the others form a background of harmonic accompaniment. If all the parts have much the same rhythm, the homophonic texture can also be described as homorhythmic. Characteristic texture of the [[Classical music|Classical period]] and continued to predominate in [[Romantic music]] while in the 20th century, \"popular music is nearly all homophonic,\" and, \"much of jazz is also\" though, \"the simultaneous improvisations of some jazz musicians creates a true polyphony\" {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=136}}. Homophonic textures usually contain only one PM {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}. HS and RS are often combined, thus labeled HRS {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n|[[File:If ye love me.png|thumb|right|250px|Homophony in [[Thomas Tallis|Tallis']] \"[[If Ye Love Me (Tallis)|If Ye Love Me]]\", composed in 1549. The voices move together using the same rhythm, and the relationship between them creates chords: the excerpt begins and ends with an F [[Major chord|major triad]].]]\n|{{Listen|filename=If ye love me.ogg|title=Tallis' \"If ye love me\"|description= Beginning of Tallis' \"If ye love me,\" notated above.|image=none|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n|-\n|[[Homorhythm]]ic\n|Multiple voices with similar rhythmic material in all parts. Also known as \"chordal\". May be considered a condition of homophony or distinguished from it.\n|see above\n|\n|-\n|[[Heterophony|Heterophonic]]\n| Two or more voices simultaneously performing variations of the same melody.\n|\n|\n|}\n\nMany classical pieces feature different kinds of texture within a short space of time.  An example is the Scherzo from [[Piano Sonata in B major, D 575 (Schubert)|Schubert\u2019s piano sonata in B major, D575]].  The first four bars are [[monophony|monophonic]], with both hands performing the same melody an octave apart:[[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 1-4.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 1\u20134]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B major scherzo bars 1-4.png|thumb|center|400px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B major scherzo bars 1\u20134 ]]\n\nBars 5\u201310 are [[homophonic]], with all voices coinciding rhythmically:[[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 5-10.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 5\u201310]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B scherzo bars 5-10.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B scherzo bars 5\u201310]]\n\nBars 11\u201320 are [[polyphonic]].  There are three parts, the top two moving in parallel (interval of a tenth). The lowest part imitates the rhythm of the upper two at the distance of three beats.  The passage climaxes abruptly with a bar\u2019s silence: [[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 11-20.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 11\u201320]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 11-20.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 11\u201320]]\n\nAfter the silence, the polyphonic texture expands from three to four independent parts moving simultaneously in bars 21\u201324. The upper two parts are [[imitation (music)|imitative]], the lowest part consists of a repeated note ([[pedal point]]) and the remaining part weaves an independent melodic line: [[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 21-24.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 21\u201324]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B majore Scherzo bars 21-24.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B majore Scherzo bars 21\u201324]]\n\nThe final four bars revert to [[homophony]], bringing the section to a close; [[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 25-28.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 25\u201328]][[File:Schubert Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 25-28.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 25\u201328]] A complete performance can be heard by following this link: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=INRxAUVLPG0 Listen]\n\n==Additional types==\nAlthough in music instruction certain styles or repertoires of music are often identified with one of these descriptions this is basically added music{{Clarify|date=September 2017}} (for example, Gregorian chant is described as monophonic, Bach Chorales are described as homophonic and fugues as polyphonic), many composers use more than one type of texture in the same piece of music.\n\nA simultaneity is more than one complete musical texture occurring at the same time, rather than in succession.\n\nA more recent type of texture first used by [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]] is [[micropolyphony]]. Other textures include polythematic, polyrhythmic, onomatopoeic, compound, and mixed or composite textures {{harv|Corozine|2002|p=34}}.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Style bris\u00e9]]\n\n==References==\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Benward & Saker|2003}}|reference=Benward, Bruce, and Marilyn Nadine Saker (2003). ''Music: In Theory and Practice'', seventh edition, vol. 1. Boston: McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|978-0-07-294262-0}}.}}\n* {{cite book |last=Corozine |first=Vince |title=Arranging Music for the Real World: Classical and Commercial Aspects |year=2002 |publisher=Mel Bay |location=Pacific, MO |isbn=0-7866-4961-5 |oclc=50470629 |ref=harv}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Hanning|1998}}|reference=[[Barbara Russano Hanning|Hanning, Barbara Russano]], ''Concise History of Western Music'', based on Donald Jay Grout & Claudia V. Palisca's ''A History of Western Music'', Fifth Edition. Published by [[W. W. Norton & Company]], New York, Copyright 1998. {{ISBN|0-393-97168-6}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Isaac & Russell|2003}}|reference=Isaac, and Russell (2003).{{Full|date=August 2015}}.}}{{Verify source|date=August 2015}}<!--No corresponding title found in LoC WorldCat.-->\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kliewer|1975}}|reference=Kliewer, Vernon (1975). \"Melody: Linear Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music\". In ''Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music'', edited by Gary Wittlich, pp.&nbsp;270\u2013301. Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey: Prentice-Hall. {{ISBN|0-13-049346-5}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kokoras|2005}}|reference=[[Panayiotis Kokoras|Kokoras, Panayiotis]] (2005). ''[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/i/icmc/bbp2372.2005.188?rgn=main;view=fulltext Towards a Holophonic Musical Texture]''. In ''Proceedings of the ICMC2005 \u2013 International Computer Music Conference'', {{Page needed|date=August 2015}}<!--Inclusive page numbers of Kokoras's paper needed.-->. Barcelona: International Computer Music Conference.}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Anon.: \"Monophony\", ''[http://www.grovemusic.com Grove Music Online]'', edited by Deane L. Root (accessed 1 August 2015) {{Subscription}}.\n* Copland, Aaron. (1957). ''What to Listen for in Music'', revised edition. New York: McGraw-Hill Book Company, Inc.\n* Demuth, Norman. 1964. ''Musical Forms and Textures: A Reference Guide'', second edition. London: Barrie and Rockliff.\n* Frobenius, Wolf, Peter Cooke, Caroline Bithell, and Izaly Zemtsovsky: \"Polyphony', ''[http://www.grovemusic.com Grove Music Online]''. edited by Deane Root (accessed 1 August 2015) {{Subscription}}.\n* Hyer, Brian: \"Homophony\", ''[http://www.grovemusic.com Grove Music Online]'', edited by Deane Root (accessed 1 August 2015) {{Subscription}}.\n* Keys, Ivor. 1961. ''The Texture of Music: From Purcell to Brahms''. London: D. Dobson.\n* White, John David. 1995. ''Theories of Musical Texture in Western History''. Perspectives in Music Criticism and Theory 1; Garland Reference Library of the Humanities 1678. New York: Garland Publishers.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.uwosh.edu/faculty_staff/liske/musicalelements/textureframes.html A Guide to Musical Texture with multimedia]\n\n{{texture (music)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Texture (Music)}}\n[[Category:Musical texture]]\n\n[[hi:]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Way in which tempo, melody, and harmony are combined in a musical composition}}\n{{Use Harvard referencing|date=December 2019}}\n[[Image:Sousa - \"Washington Post March,\" m. 1-7.png|thumb|300px|Introduction to [[John Philip Sousa|Sousa]]'s \"[[The Washington Post (march)|Washington Post March]],\" mm. 1\u20137{{audio|Sousa - \"Washington Post March,\" m. 1-7.mid|Play}} features [[octave doubling]] {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=133}} and a homorhythmic texture.]]\n\nIn [[music]], '''texture''' is how the [[tempo]], [[melody|melodic]], and [[harmony|harmonic]] materials are combined in a [[musical composition|composition]], thus determining the overall quality of the sound in a piece. Texture is often described in regard to the density, or thickness, and [[range (music)|range]], or width, between lowest and highest pitches, in relative terms as well as more specifically distinguished according to the number of voices, or parts, and the relationship between these voices (see [[#Common types|Common types]] below). For example, a thick texture contains many 'layers' of instruments. One of these layers could be a string section, or another brass. The thickness also is changed by the amount and the richness of the instruments playing the piece. The thickness varies from light to thick. A piece's texture may be changed by the number and character of parts playing at once, the [[timbre]] of the instruments or voices playing these parts and the harmony, [[tempo]], and rhythms used {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|loc={{Page needed|date=August 2015}}}}. The types categorized by number and relationship of parts are analyzed and determined through the labeling of primary textural elements: primary melody (PM), secondary melody (SM), parallel supporting melody (PSM), static support (SS), harmonic support (HS), rhythmic support (RS), and harmonic and rhythmic support (HRS) {{harv|Isaac & Russell|2003|p=136}}.\n\n==Common types==\nIn musical terms, particularly in the fields of music history and music analysis, some common terms for different types of texture are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Type\n! Description\n! Visual\n! Audio\n|-\n| [[Monophony|Monophonic]]\n| Monophonic texture includes a single melodic line with no accompaniment. {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=136}}. PSMs often double or parallel the PM they support {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n| [[Image:Pop Goes the Weasel melody.PNG|thumb|250px|\"[[Pop Goes the Weasel]]\" melody {{harv|Kliewer|1975|pp=270\u2013301}}.]]\n| {{Listen|filename=Pop Goes the Weasel.ogg|title=Pop Goes the Weasel|image=none|description=Tune for ''Pop Goes the Weasel''}}\n|-\n| Biphonic\n| Two distinct lines, the lower sustaining a drone (constant pitch) while the other line creates a more elaborate melody above it. [[Pedal point|Pedal tone]]s or [[ostinati]] would be an example of a SS {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n| [[Image:Pedal tone Bach - BWV 851, m.1-2.png|thumb|250px|Pedal tone in Bach's Prelude no. 6 in D Minor, BWV 851, from ''The Well Tempered Clavier'', Book I, mm.&nbsp;1\u20132. All pedal tone notes are consonant except for the last three of the first measure {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=99}}.]]\n| {{Listen|filename=Pedal tone Bach - BWV 851, m.1-2.mid|title=Pedal tone Bach|image=none|description=Pedal tone in Bach's Prelude no. 6 in D Minor, BWV 851, from ''The Well Tempered Clavier'', Book I, mm.&nbsp;1\u20132.}}\n|-\n|[[Polyphony|Polyphonic]] or [[Counterpoint]] or [[Contrapuntal]]\n| Multiple melodic voices which are to a considerable extent independent from or in imitation with one another. Characteristic texture of the [[Renaissance music]], also prevalent during the [[Baroque music|Baroque period]] {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|pp=1999,199,158,137, 136,129,110,90,59,35,11,9,0){{Verify source|date=August 2015}}<!--What is this, vandalism?-->}}. Polyphonic textures may contain several PMs {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n|[[File:BachFugueBar.png|thumb|right|250px|A bar from [[J.S. Bach]]'s \"[[Fugue]] No.17 in A flat\", BWV 862, from ''[[Well-tempered Clavier|Das Wohltemperirte Clavier]]'' (Part I), a famous example of '''[[counterpoint|contrapuntal polyphony]]'''. {{audio|BachFugueBar.mid|Play}}]]\n|{{Listen|filename=Johann Sebastian Bach - The Well-tempered Clavier - Book 1 - 11Efuge Bbmaj.ogg|image=none|title= Book 1 \u2013 Fugue No. 21 in B-flat major (BWV 866)|description=performed on a Flemish harpsichord by Martha Goldstein|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n|-\n|[[Homophony|Homophonic]]\n|The most common texture in Western music: melody and accompaniment. Multiple voices of which one, the melody, stands out prominently and the others form a background of harmonic accompaniment. If all the parts have much the same rhythm, the homophonic texture can also be described as homorhythmic. Characteristic texture of the [[Classical music|Classical period]] and continued to predominate in [[Romantic music]] while in the 20th century, \"popular music is nearly all homophonic,\" and, \"much of jazz is also\" though, \"the simultaneous improvisations of some jazz musicians creates a true polyphony\" {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=136}}. Homophonic textures usually contain only one PM {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}. HS and RS are often combined, thus labeled HRS {{harv|Benward & Saker|2003|p=137}}.\n|[[File:If ye love me.png|thumb|right|250px|Homophony in [[Thomas Tallis|Tallis']] \"[[If Ye Love Me (Tallis)|If Ye Love Me]]\", composed in 1549. The voices move together using the same rhythm, and the relationship between them creates chords: the excerpt begins and ends with an F [[Major chord|major triad]].]]\n|{{Listen|filename=If ye love me.ogg|title=Tallis' \"If ye love me\"|description= Beginning of Tallis' \"If ye love me,\" notated above.|image=none|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n|-\n|[[Homorhythm]]ic\n|Multiple voices with similar rhythmic material in all parts. Also known as \"chordal\". May be considered a condition of homophony or distinguished from it.\n|see above\n|\n|-\n|[[Heterophony|Heterophonic]]\n| Two or more voices simultaneously performing variations of the same melody.\n|\n|\n|}\n\nMany classical pieces feature different kinds of texture within a short space of time.  An example is the Scherzo from [[Piano Sonata in B major, D 575 (Schubert)|Schubert\u2019s piano sonata in B major, D575]].  The first four bars are [[monophony|monophonic]], with both hands performing the same melody an octave apart:[[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 1-4.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 1\u20134]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B major scherzo bars 1-4.png|thumb|center|400px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B major scherzo bars 1\u20134 ]]\n\nBars 5\u201310 are [[homophonic]], with all voices coinciding rhythmically:[[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 5-10.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 5\u201310]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B scherzo bars 5-10.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B scherzo bars 5\u201310]]\n\nBars 11\u201320 are [[polyphonic]].  There are three parts, the top two moving in parallel (interval of a tenth). The lowest part imitates the rhythm of the upper two at the distance of three beats.  The passage climaxes abruptly with a bar\u2019s silence: [[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 11-20.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 11\u201320]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 11-20.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 11\u201320]]\n\nAfter the silence, the polyphonic texture expands from three to four independent parts moving simultaneously in bars 21\u201324. The upper two parts are [[imitation (music)|imitative]], the lowest part consists of a repeated note ([[pedal point]]) and the remaining part weaves an independent melodic line: [[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 21-24.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 21\u201324]][[File:Schubert Piano Sonata in B majore Scherzo bars 21-24.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Piano Sonata in B majore Scherzo bars 21\u201324]]\n\nThe final four bars revert to [[homophony]], bringing the section to a close; [[File:Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 25-28.wav|thumb|Schubert Sonata in B scherzo bars 25\u201328]][[File:Schubert Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 25-28.png|thumb|center|500px|Schubert Sonata in B major Scherzo bars 25\u201328]] A complete performance can be heard by following this link: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=INRxAUVLPG0 Listen]\n\n==Additional types==\nAlthough in music instruction certain styles or repertoires of music are often identified with one of these descriptions this is basically added music{{Clarify|date=September 2017}} (for example, Gregorian chant is described as monophonic, Bach Chorales are described as homophonic and fugues as polyphonic), many composers use more than one type of texture in the same piece of music.\n\nA simultaneity is more than one complete musical texture occurring at the same time, rather than in succession.\n\nA more recent type of texture first used by [[Gy\u00f6rgy Ligeti]] is [[micropolyphony]]. Other textures include polythematic, polyrhythmic, onomatopoeic, compound, and mixed or composite textures {{harv|Corozine|2002|p=34}}.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Style bris\u00e9]]\n\n==References==\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Benward & Saker|2003}}|reference=Benward, Bruce, and Marilyn Nadine Saker (2003). ''Music: In Theory and Practice'', seventh edition, vol. 1. Boston: McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|978-0-07-294262-0}}.}}\n* {{cite book |last=Corozine |first=Vince |title=Arranging Music for the Real World: Classical and Commercial Aspects |year=2002 |publisher=Mel Bay |location=Pacific, MO |isbn=0-7866-4961-5 |oclc=50470629 |ref=harv}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Hanning|1998}}|reference=[[Barbara Russano Hanning|Hanning, Barbara Russano]], ''Concise History of Western Music'', based on Donald Jay Grout & Claudia V. Palisca's ''A History of Western Music'', Fifth Edition. Published by [[W. W. Norton & Company]], New York, Copyright 1998. {{ISBN|0-393-97168-6}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Isaac & Russell|2003}}|reference=Isaac, and Russell (2003).{{Full|date=August 2015}}.}}{{Verify source|date=August 2015}}<!--No corresponding title found in LoC WorldCat.-->\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kliewer|1975}}|reference=Kliewer, Vernon (1975). \"Melody: Linear Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music\". In ''Aspects of Twentieth-Century Music'', edited by Gary Wittlich, pp.&nbsp;270\u2013301. Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey: Prentice-Hall. {{ISBN|0-13-049346-5}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kokoras|2005}}|reference=[[Panayiotis Kokoras|Kokoras, Panayiotis]] (2005). ''[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/i/icmc/bbp2372.2005.188?rgn=main;view=fulltext Towards a Holophonic Musical Texture]''. In ''Proceedings of the ICMC2005 \u2013 International Computer Music Conference'', {{Page needed|date=August 2015}}<!--Inclusive page numbers of Kokoras's paper needed.-->. Barcelona: International Computer Music Conference.}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Anon.: \"Monophony\", ''[http://www.grovemusic.com Grove Music Online]'', edited by Deane L. Root (accessed 1 August 2015) {{Subscription}}.\n* Copland, Aaron. (1957). ''What to Listen for in Music'', revised edition. New York: McGraw-Hill Book Company, Inc.\n* Demuth, Norman. 1964. ''Musical Forms and Textures: A Reference Guide'', second edition. London: Barrie and Rockliff.\n* Frobenius, Wolf, Peter Cooke, Caroline Bithell, and Izaly Zemtsovsky: \"Polyphony', ''[http://www.grovemusic.com Grove Mu