riole (CB 1556)\n|(May 1960) (recorded in London)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/cb1556#comments|title=45cat \u2013 Adelaide Hall \u2013 Common Sense / Blue Bird On My Shoulder \u2013 Oriole \u2013 UK \u2013 CB 1556|work=45cat.com}}</ref>\n|Adelaide Hall\n|-\n|}\n\n===UK singles chart entries===\nSingles chart, 1940:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2561&Itemid=52|title= 1940 UK | work= Hits of All Decades \u2013 Pop rock n roll Music Chart Hits|author=Carolyn Hope}}</ref>\n* Highest chart position \u2013 Song \u2013 Artist \u2013 Peak Month\n* No. 30 \u2013 \"Careless\" by Adelaide Hall (May) \n* No. 28 \u2013 \"Begin the Beguine\" by Adelaide Hall (June) \n* No. 26 \u2013 \"All the Things You Are\" by Adelaide Hall (December)\n\nSingles chart, 1941:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2563&Itemid=52|title=1941 UK|work =Hits of All Decades \u2013Pop rock n roll Music Chart Hits|author=Carolyn Hope}}</ref>\n*No. 28 \u2013 \"Where Are You?\" by Adelaide Hall (December)\n\nSingles chart, 1945:\n*No.15 \u2013 \"There Goes That Song Again\" by Adelaide Hall (June)<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/58/a3090458.shtml \"There Goes That Song Again\" by Adelaide Hall at #15], 6 June 1944 BBC Record Chart.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[A Son of Satan]]'' (1924) (USA) (Micheaux Film)\n* ''[[Dancers in the Dark]]'' (1932) (USA) (Hall's singing voice is used but she is uncredited)\n* ''On the Air and Off'' (1933) (USA short, filmed at [[Biograph Studios]], Bronx, New York City) ([[Universal Pictures]])<ref>IMDb [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0175004/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_14 ''On the Air and Off''] (Short).</ref><ref>[https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-on-the-air-and-off-top-left-nick-lucas-top-right-adelaide-hall-bottom-72378234.html Poster for ''ON THE AIR AND OFF'' \u2013 (top left) Nick Lucas, (top right) Adelaide Hall, (bottom) Leon Belasco with Orchestra, 1933]. Alamy.</ref>\n* ''Broadway Varieties'' (1934) (USA short, filmed at [[Biograph Studios]], Bronx, New York City) ([[Universal Pictures]])<ref>IMDb [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0172194/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_13 ''Broadway Varieties''] (Short).</ref>\n* ''All-Coloured Vaudeville Show'' (1935) (USA)<ref>Ihttps://www.imdb.com/title/tt0122374/</ref>\n* ''The Kentucky Minstrels'' (1939 (British TV movie)\n* [[The Thief of Bagdad (1940 film)|''The Thief of Bagdad'']] (1940) (UK)\n* ''Behind The Blackout'' (1940), British Path\u00e9 Newsreel<ref>[http://www.britishpathe.com/video/behind-the-blackout/query/contortionists ''Behind The Blackout'' (1940)], British Path\u00e9 Newsreel.</ref>\n* ''[[Variety in Sepia]]'' (1947) (UK) ([[BBC TV]])\n* ''A World Is Turning (towards the coloured people)'' (1948) (UK)<ref>[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/580633/credits.html Adelaide Hall], BFI film listings.</ref>\n* ''Olivelli's'' (1951), British Path\u00e9 Newsreel<ref>[http://www.britishpathe.com/video/olivellis/query/adelaide+hall ''Olivelli's'' (1951)], British Path\u00e9 Newsreel.</ref>  \n* ''[[Night and the City]]'' (1959) (UK) (role \u2013 singer \u2013 the scenes were deleted from the final edit)<ref>The British Lion Film Production disc collection (held at the [[British Library]]) contains music from the film soundtrack of ''[[Night and the City]]'' on which Adelaide Hall is featured:  [http://explore.bl.uk/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?fn=search&ct=search&initialSearch=true&mode=Basic&tab=local_tab&indx=11&dum=true&srt=rank&vid=BLVU1&frbg=&tb=t&vl%28freeText0%29=adelaide+hall+night+and+the+city+&scp.scps=scope%3A%28BLCONTENT%29&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any&vl%282084770704UI0%29=title&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any \"Music for film soundtrack \u2013 Night and the City \u2013 1047X take 1 | 1046X take 7  | 1046X take 8\u201310\"]. The British Library.</ref>\n* ''Brown Sugar'' (1986) (American TV mini-series)\n* ''Sophisticated Lady'' (1989) (UK) (documentary about Adelaide Hall)\n* ''Adelaide Hall \u2013 Live at the Riverside'' (1989) (UK) (Adelaide Hall in concert)\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nExhibitions that feature or have featured content relating to Adelaide Hall:\n\n* ''Women and War'' \u2013 [[Imperial War Museum]], London (2003\u201304).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.iwm.org.uk/upload/package/41/women/displays.htm|title=Women in Wartime|work=Imperial War Museums|access-date=22 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903070140/http://archive.iwm.org.uk/upload/package/41/women/displays.htm|archive-date=3 September 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* ''Little Black Dress'' \u2013 Brighton Museum and Art Gallery, Brighton (2007).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelatest.co.uk/7/dress-is-more|title=Latest 7 \u00bb Dress is more|work=thelatest.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525201515/http://thelatest.co.uk/7/dress-is-more|archivedate=25 May 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://searchcollections.brighton-hove-rpml.org.uk/detail.php?type=related&kv=402502&t=objects Little Black Dress exhibition] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140825232222/http://searchcollections.brighton-hove-rpml.org.uk/detail.php?type=related&kv=402502&t=objects |date=25 August 2014 }}, Brighton & Hove Museum. Adelaide Hall exhibit information retrieved 24 August 2014.</ref>\n* ''Devotional'' \u2013 [[National Portrait Gallery, London]] (2007)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/devotional/adelaide_hall.html|title=National Portrait Gallery \u2013 Devotional|website=Npg.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/devotional/index.html|title=National Portrait Gallery \u2013 Devotional|work=npg.org.uk}}</ref>\n* ''Little Black Dress'' \u2013 London Fashion Museum, London (2008).<ref>[http://www.london-se1.co.uk/news/view/3363 \"Little Black Dress at the Fashion & Textile Museum\"], Sunday, 22 June 2008. London SE1 Community website.</ref>\n* ''Keep Smiling Through: Black Londoners on the Home Front 1939\u20131945'' \u2013 The Cuming Museum, London (2008).<ref>Angie Macdonald, [http://dulwichonview.org.uk/2008/04/11/keep-smiling-through/ \"Keep Smiling Through\"], 11 April 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.allinlondon.co.uk/whats-on.php?event=24385 \"Keep Smiling Through: Black Londoners on the Home Front 1939\u20131945\"], All in London.</ref>\n* ''Jazzonia and the Harlem Diaspora'' \u2013 Chelsea Space, London (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.judithwaring.com/docs/jazzoniacatalogue.pdf|title=Jazzonia and the Harlem Diaspora|website=Judithwaring.com|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>[http://www.chelseaspace.org/archive/jazzonia-pr.html \"Jazzonia & the Harlem Diaspora, Curated by Diana Rodriguez & Judith Waring\"], Chelsea Space.</ref><ref>Mike Flynn, [http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/component/content/article/51-2009/10884-art-college-hosts-jazzonia-and-the-harlem-diaspora-exhibition \"Art College Hosts Jazzonia And The Harlem Diaspora Exhibition\"], ''Jazzwise'', 8 July 2009.</ref>\n* ''The Living Archive Exhibition'' \u2013 The London Palladium (opened 2009 \u2013 on permanent display). The collection throws a spotlight on 100 years of black performers at the Palladium, such as Adelaide Hall, the Harlem Renaissance star who made her London debut at the venue in 1931.<ref>Lalayn Baluch, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2009/06/london-palladium-hosts-exhibition-celebrating-black-performance-history/ \"London Palladium hosts exhibition celebrating black performance history\"], ''The Stage'', 19 June 2009.</ref>\n* ''Oh! Adelaide'' \u2013 Art installation, Wimbledon Space, Wimbledon College of Art, London (2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nomorepotlucks.org/site/fluid-locations-discussing-archives-and-representation-with-sonia-boyce-sally-frater|title=nomorepotlucks \u00bb Fluid Locations: Discussing Archives and Representation with Sonia Boyce \u2013 Sally Frater|website=Nomorepotlucks.org}}</ref><ref>[http://vimeo.com/19976218 \"Oh Adelaide!\"] Vimeo</ref><ref>[http://www.artandeducation.net/announcement/mfah-core-exhibition-program-presents-there-is-no-archive-in-which-nothing-gets-lost/ \"There is no archive in which nothing gets lost\"]. Art & Education, 2012.</ref>\n* ''There is no Archive in which Nothing Gets Lost'' \u2013 ''Oh! Adelaide'' \u2013 Art installation \u2013 The Museum of Fine Arts, Glassell School of Art, 5101 Montrose Boulevard, Houston, America \u2013 7 September 2012 \u2013 25 November 2012.<ref>[http://www.mfah.org/exhibitions/past/there-no-archive-which-nothing-gets-lost/ \"There is no archive in which nothing gets lost\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228074414/http://www.mfah.org/exhibitions/past/there-no-archive-which-nothing-gets-lost/ |date=28 February 2013 }} Museum of Fine Arts Houston.</ref><ref>Carrie Marie Schneider, [http://glasstire.com/2012/11/04/interreview-with-sally-frater-curator-of-there-is-no-archive-in-which-nothing-gets-lost/ \"Inter(re)view with Sally Frater, curator of 'There is no archive in which nothing gets lost'\"], Glasstire, 4 November 2012.</ref>\n* ''Creole Love Call'' \u2013 Exhibition \u2013 VIERTELNEUN Gallery, 1090 Vienna, Hahngasse 14, Austria \u2013 Exhibition (25 January to 28 February 2013) \u2013 Catalogue published with the presentation.<ref>Marianne Vlaschits, [http://www.viertelneun.com/media/filer_public/2013/02/06/mediainformation_creole_love_call_by_marianne_vlaschits.pdf \"Creole Love Call\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505213751/http://www.viertelneun.com/media/filer_public/2013/02/06/mediainformation_creole_love_call_by_marianne_vlaschits.pdf |date=5 May 2014 }}, ViertelNeun Gallery.</ref>\n* ''The Harlem Renaissance'' \u2013 Kur\u00e1 Hulanda Museum, Cura\u00e7ao, Willemstad, Caribbean (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurahulanda.com/temporary-harlem-renaissance|title=Temporary: The Harlem Renaissance|work=kurahulanda.com}}</ref>\n* ''Scat: Sound and Collaboration'' \u2013 [[Iniva]] (Institute of International Visual Arts), London EC2A 3BA (5 June \u2013 27 July 2013).<ref>Sonia Boyce, [http://www.iniva.org/exhibitions_projects/2013/scat/scat \"Scat: Sound and Collaboration\"], Iniva.</ref><ref>[http://www.iniva.org/exhibitions_projects/2013/scat \"Scat: Sound and Collaboration\"], 5 June \u2013 27 July 2013, Iniva.</ref>\n* ''Untitled'' \u2013 etching by [[Sonia Boyce]]. Permanent Collection, [[Studio Museum in Harlem]], NY. In her 2006 etching ''Untitled'', Boyce pays tribute to 14 black female luminaries in British music history. Performers featured in the composition include Dame [[Shirley Bassey]], Adelaide Hall, [[Millie Small]], [[Cleo Laine]], among others.<ref>Dana Liss, [http://harlem401.rssing.com/chan-8774377/latest.php \"Permanent Collection Highlight Sonia Boyce: Untitled, 2006\"] (from the \"Rivington Place Portfolio\"). ''Studio Blog'', Studio Museum Harlem, 19 December 2013.</ref>\n* ''Black Women in Britain'', [[Black Cultural Archives]], 1 [[Windrush Square]], Brixton, London SW2 1EF (24 July \u2013 30 November 2014.<ref>[http://www.bcaheritage.org.uk/programme/reimagine/ \"Black Women in Britain\" exhibition] details website, retrieved 25 August 2014.</ref>\n* ''Rhythm & Reaction: The Age of Jazz in Britain'': Explores the emergence of Jazz in Britain and its continuing influence over the last century.<ref>Ailis Brennan, [https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/arts/celebrate-100-years-of-jazz-in-the-uk-with-a-new-exhibition-at-two-temple-place-a3753111.html \"Celebrate 100 years of jazz in the UK with a new exhibition at Two Temple Place\"], ''Evening Standard'', 30 January 2018. Retrieved 19 February 2018.</ref> Two pictures of Adelaide Hall, one by photographer [[Angus McBean]], and another extremely rare photograph of Miss Hall taken at her Florida ([[Mayfair]]) nightclub were on display at the exhibition, from 27 January 2018 until 22 April 2018, located at [[William Waldorf Astor]]'s mansion at [[Two Temple Place]], London.<ref>[https://twotempleplace.org/exhibitions/rhythm-and-reaction/ ''Rhythm & Reaction: The Age of Jazz in Britain'' (exhibition)], Two Temple Place.</ref>\n\n==Adelaide Hall Archives and Photo Collections==\n* The Indiana University Adelaide Hall Collection (1928\u20132003)<ref>[https://aaamc.indiana.edu/Collections/Adelaide-Hall \"Adelaide Hall Collection, 1928\u20132003, undated\"], Archives of African American Music and Culture, Indiana University.</ref>\nThe collection is housed at The Archives of African American Music and Culture at [[Indiana University]], collection number SC 134: The collection contains photographic materials, articles, programs and ephemera related to Hall's performance career: contact: Archives of African American Music and Culture, 2805 E 10th St., Suite 180\u2013181, Bloomington, IN 47408-4662:<ref>[http://webapp1.dlib.indiana.edu/findingaids/view?brand=general&docId=VAE0165.xml&doc.view=entire_text \"Adelaide Hall Collection, 1928\u20132003. A Guide to the collection at the Indiana University Archives of African American Music and Culture\"], Archives Online at Indiana University.</ref>\n* Writer Iain Cameron Williams and Adelaide Hall's former manager Kate Greer own a private Adelaide Hall Collection, from which items have been loaned for public exhibitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chelseaspace.org/archive/jazzonia-images1.html|title=CHELSEA space: #27 Jazzonia & the Harlem Diaspora curated by Diana Rodriguez and Judith Waring|website=Chelseaspace.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chelseaspace.org/archive/jazzonia-images2.html|title=CHELSEA space: #27 Jazzonia & the Harlem Diaspora curated by Diana Rodriguez and Judith Waring|website=Chelseaspace.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chelseaspace.org/archive/jazzonia-images3.html|title=CHELSEA space: #27 Jazzonia & the Harlem Diaspora curated by Diana Rodriguez and Judith Waring|website=Chelseaspace.org}}</ref>\n* [[Alamy]] Photo Archive: Adelaide Hall on set of the 1940 [[Alexander Korda]] directed movie [https://www.alamy.com/american-born-jazz-singer-adelaide-hall-in-costume-during-filming-of-thief-of-bagdad-1940-directors-ludwig-berger-michael-powell-tim-whelan-alexander-korda-zoltan-korda-william-cameron-menzies-screenplay-and-dialogue-miles-malleson-on-set-candid-denham-studios-england-alexander-korda-films-london-film-productions-united-artists-image264283817.html ''The Thief of Bagdad'']\n* [[Detroit Public Library]] Digital Collection houses a portrait of singer Adelaide Hall by photographer [[Germaine Krull]] dated 1929, photographed during ''Blackbirds'' residency at the [[Moulin Rouge]], [[Paris]].<ref>[https://digitalcollections.detroitpubliclibrary.org/islandora/object/islandora%3A198931 \"Portrait of singer Adelaide Hall by Germaine Krull, Paris, 1929\"].</ref>\n* [[Duke University Libraries]] \u2013 [[Rosetta Reitz]] Papers (1929\u20132008) \u2013 Adelaide Hall photograph collection series (Box 17): Rosetta Reitz Papers \u2013 Adelaide Hall Reference Materials Series (1946\u20132005) Box 36:<ref>[https://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/reitzrosetta/#aspace_ref682_ts0 Guide to the Rosetta Reitz Papers, 1929\u20132008]. Duke University Libraries.</ref>\n* [[The British Library]] in Euston Road, London, holds a considerable archive relating to Adelaide Hall; the collection contains mainly audio, interviews, live concert tapes, and recordings, some of which are quite rare.<ref>[http://explore.bl.uk/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?fn=search&ct=search&initialSearch=true&mode=Basic&tab=local_tab&indx=1&dum=true&srt=rank&vid=BLVU1&frbg=&tb=t&vl%28freeText0%29=Adelaide+Hall&scp.scps=scope%3A%28BLCONTENT%29&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any&vl%282084770704UI0%29=title&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any Adelaide Hall collections]. The British Library.</ref>\n* [[National Portrait Gallery, London]] (Archive) holds two Adelaide Hall portraits from the 1940s:<ref>[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp86268/adelaide-hall \"Adelaide Hall (1901\u20131993), Singer and actress\"]. NPG, London (archive).</ref>\n* [[Getty Images]] (archive) holds several photographs of Adelaide Hall including one of her singing 'There's Something in the Air' at her [[Mayfair]] nightclub (the Florida Club) in [[London]], circa. 1945:<ref>[https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/adelaide-hall-singing-theres-something-in-the-air-at-a-news-photo/3270557 \"Adelaide Hall Sings: circa 1945: Adelaide Hall (1901\u20131993) singing 'There's Something In The Air' at a bottle party in the Florida nightclub. The pianist is Fela Sowande\"]. Photo by Hulton Archive/Getty Images.</ref> and an extremely rare picture of Miss Hall performing in concert circa.1930,<ref>[https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/jazz-singer-adelaide-hall-in-concert-circa-1930-news-photo/914926230 \"Adelaide Hall: Jazz singer Adelaide Hall (1901\u20131993) in concert, circa 1930\"]. Photo by Fox Photos/Hulton Archive/Getty Images.</ref> and a portrait photograph of Miss Hall by John D. Kisch circa. 1934<ref>[https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/publicity-still-of-american-jazz-singer-and-harlem-news-photo/153542543 Adelaide Hall portrait], photograph by John D. Kisch, 1934.</ref>\n* The Al Hirschfeld Foundation holds two caricatures of Adelaide Hall by the artist [[Al Hirschfeld]], one dated 1928<ref>[http://www.alhirschfeldfoundation.org/piece/blackbirds-1928 \"Blackbirds Of 1928\"]. Adelaide Hall caricature by Al Hirschfeld, published 7 May 1928.</ref> and the other dated 1929.<ref>[http://www.alhirschfeldfoundation.org/piece/blackbirds#result_info_7722 \"Blackbirds\"]. Adelaide Hall caricature by Al Hirschfeld, published 5 May 1929.</ref>\n* Museo Alinari Image (AIM), museum, Trieste, Italy, hold two portrait photographs of Adelaide Hall ca. 1925\u201329:<ref>[https://www.alinari.it/en/detail/PPA-F-001937-0000?search=059a37224151e5e4e94ecdb2bd28a17a&searchPos=5 Full-length portrait of Adelaide Hall, 1929 by photographer Manuel G. L. Freres], Alinari Images (Archive).</ref><ref>[https://www.alinari.it/en/detail/PPA-F-001967-0000 Head portrait of Adelaide Hall, 1925 unknown photographer], Alinari Images (Archive).</ref>\n* [[Millersville University]] Special Collection: Adelaide Hall, File \u2013 Box: 4, Folder 21, 1929 photograph of Miss Hall by Walery (aka [[Stanis\u0142aw Julian Ignacy Ostror\u00f3g]]).<ref>[https://millersville.as.atlas-sys.com/repositories/2/archival_objects/36103 \"Adelaide Hall, 1928\"], [[Millersville University]] Special Collection.</ref>\n* ''The British Lion Film Production disc'' collection (held at the [[British Library]]) contains music from the film soundtrack of ''[[Night and the City]]'' on which Adelaide Hall is featured:<ref>[http://explore.bl.uk/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?fn=search&ct=search&initialSearch=true&mode=Basic&tab=local_tab&indx=11&dum=true&srt=rank&vid=BLVU1&frbg=&tb=t&vl%28freeText0%29=adelaide+hall+night+and+the+city+&scp.scps=scope%3A%28BLCONTENT%29&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any&vl%282084770704UI0%29=title&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any \"Music for film soundtrack \u2013 Night and the City \u2013 1047X take 1 | 1046X take 7  | 1046X take 8\u201310\"]. The British Library.</ref>\n* ''The David Lund Collection'' held at the British Library contains live audio recordings of Adelaide Hall in concert with The [[Alan Clare]] Trio and John McLeary performing at the [[University College School]] Theatre, Hampstead, London<ref>[http://explore.bl.uk/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?tabs=moreTab&ct=display&fn=search&doc=BLLSA7686062&indx=63&recIds=BLLSA7686062&recIdxs=2&elementId=2&renderMode=poppedOut&displayMode=full&frbrVersion=2&frbg=&dscnt=0&vl(2084770704UI0)=any&scp.scps=scope%3A%28BLCONTENT%29&tb=t&mode=Basic&vid=BLVU1&srt=rank&tab=local_tab&dum=true&vl(freeText0)=Adelaide%20Hall%20&dstmp=1548846004363 \"David Lund Collection | Adelaide Hall with The Alan Clare Trio and John McLeary\"], The British Library.</ref>\n* [[Smithsonian]] \u2013 [https://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.91.199.1C?destination=node/63231%3Fedan_q%3Dadelaide%2520hall Adelaide Hall] portrait \u2013 ''Le Tumulte Noir'' / Dancer in Magenta by [[Paul Colin (artist)|Paul Colin]], 1929, Paris, at the [[Smithsonian]], National Portrait Gallery Collection, [[Washington D.C.]]<ref>Lithograph with pochoir coloring on paper\n\u00a9 1997 Estate of Paul Colin / Artists Rights Society (ARS), New York / ADAGP, Paris: Object Number: NPG.91.199.1C, Smithsonian, National Portrait Gallery Collection, Washington D.C.</ref>\n* The [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] ([[V&A]]), South Kensington, [[London]], holds a watercolour caricature of Adelaide Hall by Gilbert Sommerlad, dated 12 May 1954, drawn during Hall's starring role in the musical ''Love from Judy'',<ref name=Sommerlad /> plus various posters relating to Miss Hall's career, and a cotton souvenir headscarf containing a printed portrait of Adelaide Hall ca.1930s\u201350s.<ref>[http://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O11200/headscarf/ Souvenir cotton headscarf containing a printed picture of Adelaide Hall on it ca. 1930s\u20131950s]. V&A Theatre and Performance Collection.</ref>\n* [[Yale University Library]] \u2013 Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library: Rare Adelaide Hall photographs by [[Carl Van Vechten]] taken of Miss Hall performing on stage during her 1931/1932 World Tour at the [[Palace Theatre (New York City)|Palace Theatre]], Times Square, New York.<ref>[https://brbl-dl.library.yale.edu/vufind/Record/3532399 \"Adelaide Hall on the stage of the Palace Theatre\"], Beinecke Digital Collections.</ref>\n* Yale University Library \u2013 Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library: Adelaide Hall publicity photographs collected by writer and photographer [[Carl Van Vechten]].<ref>[https://brbl-dl.library.yale.edu/vufind/Record/4161882 \"Adelaide Hall\"], Beinecke Digital Collections.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* Find A Grave [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7979544/ adelaide-louise-hall]\n{{Portal bar|United States|UK|Music|Jazz|biography}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [[Ian Carr]], [[Digby Fairweather]] and [[Brian Priestley]]. ''Jazz: The Rough Guide''. {{ISBN|1-85828-528-3}}\n* Iain Cameron Williams. [http://www.bloomsbury.com/us/underneath-a-harlem-moon-9780826458933/ ''Underneath a Harlem Moon: The Harlem to Paris Years of Adelaide Hall'']. Bloomsbury Publishers, {{ISBN|0-8264-5893-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0355263}}\n* Lucy Shacklock, [https://www.africansinyorkshireproject.com/adelaide-hall.html \"Adelaide Hall\"], African Stories in Hull & East Yorkshire.\n<!--already in Sources* [http://www.bloomsbury.com/us/underneath-a-harlem-moon-9780826458933/ Iain Cameron Williams, ''Underneath A Harlem Moon: The Harlem to Paris years of Adelaide Hall''] at Bloomsbury Publishing.-->\n{{commons|Adelaide Hall}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Adelaide}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American female dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American people who self-identify as being of Native American descent]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American tap dancers]]\n[[Category:British female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Cemetery of the Evergreens]]\n[[Category:Cabaret singers]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Entertainments National Service Association personnel]]\n[[Category:Harlem Renaissance]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Music hall performers]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People of Montmartre]]\n[[Category:RCA Victor artists]]\n[[Category:Scat singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Torch singers]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dancers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American-born UK-based jazz singer and entertainer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Adelaide Hall\n| image               = Adelaide Hall 01.jpg\n| caption             = \n| birth_name          = Adelaide Louise Hall\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|df=yes|1901|10|20}}<ref>[http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.J184500 State records] confirm Adelaide Hall's year of birth as 1901.</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|1993|11|07|1901|10|20}}\n| death_place         =  [[London]], England\n| other_names         = \n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*musician\n*actress\n*dancer\n*nightclub chanteuse\n}}\n| years_active  = 1921\u20131992      \n| children      = \n| spouse        = {{marriage|Bertram Hicks<br />|1924|1963|reason=d.}}\n| relatives     = \n| module = {{infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| instrument          = {{hlist|Vocals|[[ukulele]]|acoustic guitar}}\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Jazz]]|[[Swing music|swing]]|[[traditional pop]]|[[spirituals]]|musical theatre}}\n| origin              = \n| label               = {{Flatlist|\n*Victor\n*[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n*Brunswick\n*[[Sony Music|CBS]]\n*[[Lucky Records|Lucky]]\n*Decca\n*[[London Records|London]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[Art Tatum]]|[[Ethel Waters]]|[[Josephine Baker]]|[[Louis Armstrong]]|[[Lena Horne]]|[[Cab Calloway]]|[[Duke Ellington]]|[[Fats Waller]]}}\n| website             = \n}}\n}}\n'''Adelaide Louise Hall''' (20 October 1901 \u2013 7 November 1993) was an American-born UK-based jazz singer and entertainer. Her long career spanned more than 70 years from 1921 until her death and she was a major figure in the [[Harlem Renaissance]].<ref name=Voce>{{cite news|author=Steve Voce |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-adelaide-hall-1502902.html |title=Obituary: Adelaide Hall|work=The Independent |date=8 November 1993 |accessdate=15 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Glenn Collins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/10/obituaries/adelaide-hall-92-international-star-of-cabaret.html |title=Adelaide Hall, 92, International Star of Cabaret|date=10 November 1993 |accessdate=15 June 2012 |work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/adelaide-hall-38526 |title=Adelaide Hall Biography \u2013 Facts, Birthday, Life Story |website=Biography.com |date=7 November 1993 |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=ICWilliams>{{cite book |url=http://www.bloomsbury.com/us/underneath-a-harlem-moon-9780826458933/|author=Iain Cameron Williams|title=Underneath a Harlem Moon: The Harlem to Paris Years of Adelaide Hall |isbn= 0-8264-5893-9|date=15 September 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian2003\">{{cite news|author=Stephen Bourne |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/biography.music |title=The real first lady of jazz (Review of ''Underneath a Harlem Moon'' by Iain Cameron Williams) |work=The Guardian |date= 24 January 2003|accessdate=15 June 2012 |location=London|author-link=Stephen Bourne (writer) }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/artist/bio/adelaide-hall/440138 |title=Adelaide Hall Biography |website=Artistdirect.com |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref> Hall entered the ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' in 2003 as the world's most enduring recording artist having released material over eight consecutive decades.<ref name=Devotonal>[http://www.npg.org.uk/devotional/honours.html \"Devotees \u2013 Honours and Tributes\"] (researched and compiled by Stephen Bourne), Devotional. Adelaide Hall enters ''Guinness Book of World Records'' as the World's most enduring recording artiste.</ref> She performed with major artists such as [[Art Tatum]],<ref>{{YouTube|VhMq8_s64Y4|\"Art Tatum \u2013 Strange As It Seems (1933)\"}}.</ref> [[Ethel Waters]], [[Josephine Baker]], [[Louis Armstrong]], [[Lena Horne]], [[Cab Calloway]], [[Fela Sowande]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalopus.com/cgi-bin/io.pl?mode=composer&composer=28|title=International Opus|work=internationalopus.com}}</ref> [[Rudy Vallee]]<ref name=\"Don't Call Them Crooners\" /> and [[Jools Holland]], and recorded as a jazz singer with [[Duke Ellington]] (with whom she made her most famous recording, \"[[Creole Love Call]]\" in 1927)<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jPO5VDoDGLM Adelaide Hall singing \"Creole Love Call\" with Duke Ellington and his Orchestra] recorded in 1927. YouTube.</ref> and with [[Fats Waller]].<ref name=\"kennedy-center1\"/><ref name=WallerBroadcasts />\n\n==Early life and marriage==\nAdelaide Hall was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York, United States, to Elizabeth and Arthur William Hall in 1901. Adelaide and her sister Evelyn attended the [[Pratt Institute]], where William Hall taught piano; Evelyn was to die of influenza in 1918, by which time her father had also died, and the teenaged Hall had to support herself and her mother.<ref>Bruce Eder, [https://www.allmusic.com/artist/adelaide-hall-mn0000929857/biography \"Artist Biography\"] at Allmusic.</ref><ref name=Voce />\n\nHall began her stage career in 1921 on Broadway in the chorus line of [[Noble Sissle]]'s and [[Eubie Blake]]'s hit musical ''[[Shuffle Along]]''<ref name=\"kennedy-center1\">{{Cite web|url=http://artsedge.kennedy-center.org/interactives/harlem/faces/adelaide_hall.html|title=ARTSEDGE: Drop Me Off in Harlem|website=Artsedge.kennedy-center.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpast.org/?q=aah/shuffle-along-1921 |title=Shuffle Along (1921) &#124; The Black Past: Remembered and Reclaimed |publisher=The Black Past|date=16 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicals101.com/1920bway3.htm |title=Stage Musicals 1920s \u2013 Part 3: New Composers |website=Musicals101.com |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artsedge.kennedy-center.org/interactives/harlem/themes/shuffle_along.html|title=ARTSEDGE: Drop Me Off in Harlem|website=Artsedge.kennedy-center.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reside |first=Doug |url=http://www.nypl.org/blog/2012/02/10/musical-month-shuffle-along |title=Musical of the Month: Shuffle Along|publisher=The New York Public Library |date=10 February 2012 |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref> and went onto appear in a number of similar black musical shows including ''[[James P. Johnson#Composer|Runnin' Wild]]''<ref>{{cite web|author=The Broadway League |url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=9308 |title=Runnin' Wild|publisher=IBDB: The official source for Broadway Information |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref> on Broadway in 1923, in which she sang [[James P. Johnson]]'s hit song \"Old-Fashioned Love.\" In 1925, Hall toured Europe with the ''Chocolate Kiddies'' revue that included songs written by [[Duke Ellington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chevalierdesaintgeorges.homestead.com/ellington.html |title=Edward K. \"Duke\" Ellington, African American Composer & Pianist |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref> In 1926, Hall appeared in the short-lived Broadway musical ''My Magnolia'', which had a score written by [[Luckey Roberts]] and Alex C. Rogers,<ref>Todd Decker, ''Show Boat: Performing Race in an American Musical'' by Oxford University Press, 2013, p. 107 ({{ISBN|978-0-19-975937-8}}), mentions the musical ''My Magnolia''.</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XFnfnKg6BcAC&pg=PA472&lpg=PA472 |title=Vaudeville, Old and New: An Encyclopedia of Variety Performers in America|author=Frank Cullen |publisher=Psychology Press|year=2004|isbn=9780415938532}}</ref> after which she appeared in ''Tan Town Topics'' with songs written by [[Fats Waller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19260417&id=ZxomAAAAIBAJ&pg=4392,5036180|title=The Afro American \u2013 Google News Archive Search|work=google.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.areditions.com/rr/embellish/2001_15/feature.html |title=Thomas \"Fats\" Waller: Performances in Transcription, edited by Paul S. Machlin |website=Areditions.com |accessdate=15 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528073952/https://www.areditions.com/rr/embellish/2001_15/feature.html |archivedate=28 May 2013  }}</ref> Hall then starred in ''Desires of 1927'' (with a score written by [[Andy Razaf]] and [[J. C. Johnson]]),<ref>''Desires of 1927'' musical, p. 106, ''A Century of Musicals in Black and White: An Encyclopedia of Musical Stage'' by Bernard L. Peterson, Greenwood Publishing Group. {{ISBN|0-313-26657-3}}</ref> which toured America from October 1926 through to September 1927.<ref>[[Henry Louis Gates]], Evelyn Brooks Higginbotham (eds), [https://books.google.com/books?id=E_vRLcgEdGoC&pg=PA233 ''Harlem Renaissance Lives from the African American National Biography''], Oxford University Press, 2009, p. 233.</ref><ref name=DesiresReview>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1112695542.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+27%2C+1926&author=&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=A2&desc=%27DESIRES+OF+1927%27+A+RIOT+AT+ELMORE%3B+%27DIXIE+BREVITIES%27+... \"'Desires of 1927' \u2013 A Riot at Elmore\" (review)], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 27 November 1926.</ref>\n\nIn 1924, Hall married a British sailor named Bertram Errol Hicks, who was born in [[Trinidad and Tobago]]. Soon after their marriage he opened a short-lived club in [[Harlem, New York]], called \"The Big Apple\" and became her official business manager.<ref>Bratkovich, Colin, ''Just Remember This'', publ. Xlibris 2014, {{ISBN|978-1483645186}}, p. 84 \u2013 Big Apple, 135th and Seventh Avenue, Uptown Harlem, NYC, associated with Adelaide Hall, 1924. The term 'Big Apple' became associated with the whole of NYC.</ref>\n\n==Career 1925\u20131938==\n===''Chocolate Kiddies'' European tour, 1925===\nHall was hired to join the cast of the ''Chocolate Kiddies'' revue in New York, where they rehearsed before setting sail for Europe. The initial tour started at [[Hamburg]], Germany, on 17 May 1925, and ended in Paris, France in December 1925 visiting many major cities in-between.<ref>[http://keepswinging.blogspot.co.uk/2006/05/maestro-sam-wooding-y-sus-chocolate.html Article about Sam Wooding and the Chocolate Kiddies], ''Keep (It) Swinging'', 11 May 2006.</ref> The revue was designed to give Europeans a sampling of black entertainment from New York.<ref>{{cite book|author=Chip Deffaa|title=Voices of the Jazz Age: Profiles of Eight Vintage Jazzmen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xJB16RjX3z8C&pg=PA14|year=1992|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-06258-2|page=14}}</ref> Included in the cast were The Three Eddies, [[Lottie Gee]], Rufus Greenlee and Thaddeus Drayton, Bobbie and Babe Goins, Charles Davis and [[Sam Wooding]] and his Orchestra. After the initial tour disbanded, [[Sam Wooding]] and his Orchestra continued touring the ''Chocolate Kiddies'' revue for several years later. During Hall's visit to Germany she also sang at [[Berlin]]'s renowned transvestite club, the Eldorado Caf\u00e9.<ref>Colin Bratkovich, ''Just Remember This'', Xlibris, 2014, p. 148, {{ISBN|1483645185}}. Retrieved 17 August 2018.</ref> The venue is immortalised in [[Christopher Isherwood]]'s novel ''[[Goodbye to Berlin]]'' and in the 1972 film [[Cabaret (1972 film)|''Cabaret'']] and the [[Cabaret (musical)|musical]] of the same name.<ref>[https://1920sberlinproject.wordpress.com/2011/07/26/the-eldorado/ \"The Eldorado\"], ''The 1920s Berlin Project''. Retrieved 17 December 2018.</ref>\n\n===''Tan Town Topics'', Small's Paradise and ''Desires of 1927''===\nIn 1926, upon Hall's return to New York after touring Europe with the ''Chocolate Kiddies'', she was featured in ''Tan Town Topics'', a revue containing songs written by [[Fats Waller]] and [[Spencer Williams]]. The cast included [[Fats Waller]], Eddie Rector and [[Ralph Cooper (actor)|Ralph Cooper]], Adelaide Hall, Maude Mills, Arthur Gaines, Leondus Simmons and a dance troupe called the Tan Town Topics Vamps. The show opened at Harlem's [[Lafayette Theatre (Harlem)|Lafayette Theatre]] on 5 April followed by a short road tour on the eastern [[Theater Owners Booking Association]] (TOBA) circuit taking in [[Baltimore]], [[Chicago]] and [[Philadelphia]].<ref>12 \u2013 17 April 1926, Royal Theatre, Baltimore City. 10 April 1926, ''The Afro-American'', p. 10, half-page advertisement for ''Tan Town Topics''.</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19260417&id=ZxomAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v_0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4392,5036180 Review of ''Tan Town Topics''] at the Royal Theatre, Baltimore.</ref>\n\nDuring July 1926, Hall appeared in residency with Lottie Gee and the [[Southern Syncopated Orchestra]] at Small's Paradise, New York.<ref>Howard Rye, [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/black_music_research_journal/v030/30.1.rye01.html#fig01 \"Southern Syncopated Orchestra: The Roster\"], ''Black Music Research Journal'', Volume 30, Number 1, Spring 2010. Reference to Smalls Paradise revue under \"Gee, Lottie (Charlotte M.)\".</ref> On Tuesday, 5 October, Hall appeared again at Small's Paradise at a special party, \"Handy Night\", hosted by the venue to honour [[W. C. Handy]] and to celebrate the release of his newly published book ''Blues: An Anthology\u2014Complete Words and Music of 53 Great Songs''. For entertainment, Adelaide Hall, Lottie Gee, Maude White and Chic Collins provided a selection of jazz and blues numbers.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/40138126/ \"'Handy Night' at Small\u2019s Paradise\"], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', Saturday, 16 October 1926, p. 10.</ref> From October 1926, Hall toured America playing the TOBA circuit until September 1927 in the highly praised show ''Desires of 1927'', conceived by [[J. Homer Tutt]] and produced by impresario [[Irvin C. Miller]]. As the ''[[Pittsburgh Courier]]'' noted: \"Adelaide Hall and assistants have some show. Speed, pretty girls, catchy music, a touch of art, which touches the border line of nudity \u2013 the names of such well-known stage celebrities as Adelaide Hall, [[J. Homer Tutt]], Henry \"Gang\" Jones, the Harmony, Trio, Charles Hawkins, Arthur Porter, \"Billy\" McKelvey and Clarence Nance.\"<ref name=DesiresReview /> Billed as the star \"soubrette\" of the show, Adelaide's performance included several songs (most notably \"Sweet Virginia Bliss\"), flat-foot dancing and accompanying herself on the ukulele while singing.\n\n===Recordings with Duke Ellington===\nIn October 1927, Hall recorded her wordless vocals on \"[[Creole Love Call]]\", \"The Blues I Love To Sing\" and \"Chicago Stomp Down\" with [[Duke Ellington]] and his Orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/DukeEllingtonOrchVadelaideHall-CreoleLoveCall |title=Duke Ellington Orch, V=Adelaide Hall \u2013 Creole Love Call : Adelaide Hall : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |website=Archive.org |date=10 March 2001 |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref> The recordings were worldwide hits and catapulted both Hall's and Ellington's careers into the mainstream.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x8jpl3_adelaide-hall-talks-about-the-cotto_music |title=Adelaide Hall talks about the Cotton Club and Duke Ellington \u2013 Video Dailymotion |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1993-11-08/news/mn-54492_1_duke-ellington |title=Adelaide Hall, 92; Jazz Singer Performed With Duke Ellington |work=Los Angeles Times|date=22 May 2001 |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref> For historical reasons the story behind \"[[Creole Love Call]]\"'s conception is interesting to recount: In 1927, Hall and [[Duke Ellington]] were touring in the same show, ''Dance Mania''. The show played several large cities before reaching [[New York City]]. In mid-November, Adelaide travelled from [[Chicago]] (where she'd been performing) to [[New York City]] in her [[Packard]] automobile with her husband Bert. When they arrived in New York, Adelaide was approached in 7th Avenue by a reporter who enquired about her career plans.<ref>''The Pittsburgh Courier'', Pittsburgh, 19 November 1927, front page \u2013 'They Always Come Back For More,\u2019 says Adelaide \u2013 Adelaide Hall report & photograph: https://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=30987648&fcfToken=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJmcmVlLXZpZXctaWQiOjQwMDA3ODExLCJpYXQiOjE1NzE0ODQ5NTEsImV4cCI6MTU3MTU3MTM1MX0.vQF9B_O3GWoXhj74SJP8_ICp4wIHl4jUNTrlrvKpgf0</ref> Adelaide, however, declined to enlighten the reporter. Nevertheless, Miss Hall's reappearance in [[New York City]] garnered much speculation, as she was featured on the front pages of several newspapers, encouraging rumours she would soon be starring in a big [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] show. In the meantime, Hall and Ellington appeared together in ''Dance Mania'' at the [[Lafayette Theatre (Harlem)|Lafayette Theatre]], Harlem from 14 November for one week before heading off with the show to play in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at the Standard Theatre.<ref>[http://www.ellingtonweb.ca/Hostedpages/TDWAW/DropdownmenuDRAFT.html#dec27 ''Dance Mania'' dates] listed on Ellingtonweb.</ref> In ''Dance Mania'' Hall closed the first half of the bill and Duke and his orchestra performed in the second half. Duke had a new number \"[[Creole Love Call]]\", which he included in his set. When Adelaide first heard the number back in October, she recounted, \n<blockquote>I was standing in the wings behind the piano when Duke first played it (\"[[Creole Love Call]]\"). I started humming along with the band. He stopped the number and came over to me and said, \"That's just what I was looking for. Can you do it again?\" I said, \"I can't, because I don't know what I was doing.\" He begged me to try. Anyway, I did, and sang this counter melody, and he was delighted and said \"Addie, you're going to record this with the band.\" A couple of days later I did.<ref name=Voce /></blockquote> \n[[File:Cotton Club 1930.jpg|thumb|[[Cotton Club]], [[Harlem]]]]\nWhen Duke was recounting the incident to a reporter he explained, \"We had to do something to employ Adelaide Hall,\" and then added, \"I always say we are primitive artists, we only employ the materials at hand \u2026 the band is an accumulation of personalities, tonal devices.\"<ref>David Bradbury, ''Duke Ellington'', Haus Publishing Ltd, 2005 ({{ISBN|1-904341-66-7}}), p. 19.</ref> On 4 December 1927, Ellington and his Orchestra commenced their residency at Harlem's [[Cotton Club]] in a revue called ''Rhythmania''. The show featured Hall singing \"[[Creole Love Call]]\".<ref>Williams, [http://www.bloomsbury.com/us/underneath-a-harlem-moon-9780826458933/ ''Underneath A Harlem Moon''], Chapter 8, pp. 122\u201324.</ref> In 1928, \"[[Creole Love Call]]\" entered the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' song charts at No. 19 (USA).<ref>[http://tsort.info/music/sht3ur.htm USA song chart entry for \"\"Creole Love Call\"] (1928).</ref> On 7 January 1933, Hall and Duke Ellington and his Famous Orchestra recorded \"I Must Have That Man\" and \"Baby\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.depanorama.net/33.htm|title=Ellington Sessions 1933|work=depanorama.net}}</ref>\n\n===''Blackbirds of 1928''===\n[[File:Adelaide Hall 1921.jpg|thumb|left|Adelaide Hall in [[Blackbirds of 1928]]]]\nIn 1928, Hall starred on Broadway with [[Bill \"Bojangles\" Robinson]],<ref>[http://artsedge.kennedy-center.org/interactives/harlem/faces/bill_robinson.html \"Faces of the Harlem Renaissance \u2013 Bill 'Bojangles' Robinson\"], Drop Me Off in Harlem.</ref> [[Tim Moore (comedian)|Tim Moore]] and [[Aida Ward]] in ''[[Blackbirds of 1928]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masterworksbroadway.com/music/blackbirds-of-1928-shuffle-along-1921|title=Blackbirds of 1928 / Shuffle Along (1921) \u2013 The Official Masterworks Broadway Site|work=The Official Masterworks Broadway Site}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancientfaces.com/research/photo/417031/adelaide-hall-family-photo|title=Adelaide Hall|author=Daniel Pinna|work=ancientfaces.com}}</ref> The show became the most successful all-black show ever staged on Broadway at that time and made Hall and Bojangles into household names.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19290518&id=3WNGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=feUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3694,6655659 \"''Blackbirds of 1928'' celebrates one year run on Broadway\"], ''The Afro-American'', 18 May 1929. Retrieved 14 September 2014.</ref> ''Blackbirds of 1928'' was the idea of impresario [[Lew Leslie]], who planned to build the show around [[Florence Mills]] in New York after her success in the hit London show ''Blackbirds'' but Mills died of [[pneumonia]] in 1927 before rehearsals commenced. Hall was chosen to replace her. The revue opened at Les Ambassadeurs Club in New York in January 1928, under the name ''Blackbird Revue'', but it was renamed ''Blackbirds of 1928'' and in May 1928 transferred to Broadway's [[Liberty Theatre (New York City)|Liberty Theatre]],<ref name=\"performingartsarchive.com\">{{cite web | url = http://www.performingartsarchive.com/Theatres/Theatres-L/Liberty-Theatre_NYC/Liberty-Theatre_NYC.htm | title = Liberty NYC Performing Arts Archive | author = Danni Bayles Yeager | work = performingartsarchive.com}}</ref> where it ran for 518 performances. After a slow start, the show became the hit of the season. Hall's performance of \"Diga Diga Do\", created a sensation. Her mother was so incensed when she went to see the show by her daughter performing what she termed 'risqu\u00e9 dance moves', she tried to stop the show during Adelaide's performance and banned her from appearing in any future performances. The ban only remained for one performance and Adelaide returned triumphantly to her role the following day.<ref name=DazedMother/> It was reported in the press of the day that the show's producer [[Lew Leslie]] was so concerned about race violence connected with the controversy surrounding Adelaide's performance that he took out a hefty insurance policy to cover the cast; the most heavily insured were the principals, Adelaide Hall and \"Bojangles\" Robinson.<ref>\"Adelaide Hall returns to cast of ''Blackbirds''\", ''Chicago Defender'', 11 August 1928.</ref> It was this musical that not only secured Hall's success in the USA but also in Europe when the production was taken in 1929 to [[Paris]], France, where it ran for four months at the [[Moulin Rouge]].<ref>Judith Miller, [https://books.google.com/books?id=QaDjoWtemXgC&pg=PA215 ''Art Deco''], Dorling Kindersley, 2005, {{ISBN|1405307544}}: lithograph by Paul Colin featuring Adelaide Hall and used as a poster to advertise ''Blackbirds'' at the [[Moulin Rouge]], p. 215. Retrieved 14 September 1014.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/2003_02_wed_03.shtml ''Woman's Hour'' Music Archive]: A Celebration of Adelaide Hall, Wednesday, 15 January 2003.</ref><ref>Jean Delaurier 1929 [http://www.bridgemanart.com/de/asset/224685/delaurier-jean-fl-1930/the-black-birds-band-in-the-moulin-rouge-revue-porgy-illustration-from-l-art-vivant-1st-august-1929-litho-b-w-photo lithograph] of Blackbirds at the Moulin Rouge performing \"Porgy\",</ref> When Adelaide Hall arrived in Paris from America at the [[Gare Saint-Lazare]] she was greeted by a reception of fans and reporters that was reported to be as large as the reception [[Charlie Chaplin]] had received two years earlier when he visited Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music6cafe.com/2014/12/|title=December 2014|website=Music6cafe.com|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> The French artist [[Paul Colin (artist)|Paul Colin]] illustrated several posters to advertise ''Blackbirds'' run at the Moulin Rouge including one entitled \"Le Tumulte Noir \u2013 Dancer in Magenta\" that captures Hall's performance beautifully, as she is dancing and waving her arms about.<ref>[http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?q=record_ID:npg_NPG.91.199.1C \"Le Tumulte Noir/Dancer in Magenta\"], artist Paul Colin's lithograph of Adelaide Hall.</ref> An original vintage poster of Adelaide Hall by [[Paul Colin (artist)|Paul Colin]] advertising ''Blackbirds'' at the Moulin Rouge sold on 2 October 2003 at [[Swann Auction Galleries]] in New York for $167,500.<ref>[http://catalogue.swanngalleries.com/asp/fullCatalogue.asp?salelot=1978++++++44+&refno=++530774&saletype= The Chassaing Collection of French Art Deco Posters Auction] at Swann Auction Galleries in New York, catalogue 2 October 2003.</ref> In Europe, Hall rivalled [[Josephine Baker]] for popularity on the European stage.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0R0mAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1f0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6858,814569&dq=adelaide+hall&hl=en \"Adelaide Hall Takes Place of 'Jo' Baker\"], ''The Afro-American'', 3 August 1929.</ref>\n\n[[File:Vu (magazine) N\u00b077.JPG|thumb|''Vu'' (magazine), issue N\u00b077 ''Au revoir Black Birds!'' (04 09 1929). Adelaide Hall on the front cover of [[Vu (magazine)|Vu]] as the French say farewell to ''Blackbirds'' after their tenure at the [[Moulin Rouge]].]]\nWith ''Blackbirds''\u2032 music score written by [[Jimmy McHugh]] and lyrics by [[Dorothy Fields]], Hall's performances of the songs \"[[I Can't Give You Anything but Love, Baby]]\", \"Diga Diga Do\",<ref name=DazedMother>Theophilus Lewis, [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1109974732.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+10%2C+1928&author=Theophilus+Lewis&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=B2&desc=THE+DANCE+THAT+DAZED+MOTHER \"THE DANCE THAT DAZED MOTHER \u2013 \"DIGA DIGA DO\"--AS DANCED BY ADELAIDE HALL\u2014CREATES SENSATION. \"STOP IT!\" CRIES MAMA. \"ON WITH THE DANCE\" BROADWAY DEMANDS\"], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 10 November 1928.</ref> \"Bandanna Babies\" and \"I Must Have That Man\" made them into household hits, and they continued to be audience favourites throughout her long career. At the end of ''Blackbirds'' tenure at the Moulin Rouge, to thank the cast for their successful run and to welcome in the forthcoming [[Thanksgiving Day]], Lew Leslie threw a big party held in the Paris suburb of Authie and, as well as the cast, invited a host of visiting luminaries including the visual artist [[Man Ray]], lyricist [[Ira Gershwin]], writer [[James Joyce]], German composer [[Kurt Weill]], American composer [[William Grant Still]] and producer Clarence Robinson. A rare group photograph taken at the event in which Adelaide Hall is seated in the centre surrounded by guests including actress and music hall star [[Mistinguett]], recently surfaced and was sold at Swann Auction Galleries, New York for $2,640.<ref>[http://catalogue.swanngalleries.com/asp/fullCatalogue.asp?salelot=2239+++++391+&refno=++642162&saletype= Swann Auction Gallery, New York, Sale 2239 Lot 391]. Group photograph of the 'Blackbirds' party, 1929, taken at Authie, Paris. Retrieved 1 January 2015.</ref> \nThe ''Blackbirds'' cast sailed from France back to the US in the fall of 1929 and upon their arrival almost immediately commenced a road tour of the States opening at the Adelphi Theatre, Chicago, on the evening of 26 November. It was in Chicago during December that Adelaide Hall unexpectedly quit the production and hastened home to New York.\n[[File:Adelaide Hall c. 1920.jpg|thumb|Adelaide Hall in [[Blackbirds of 1928]]]]\n\n===1930: ''Brown Buddies''===\nSpeculation that Hall and [[Bill \"Bojangles\" Robinson]] would be paired up on stage again after Hall quit ''Blackbirds'' at the end of 1929 had been rife amongst theatrical circles and in newspaper gossip columns.<ref>[http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%2023/Pittsburgh%20PA%20Courier/Pittsburgh%20PA%20Courier%201929-1930/Pittsburgh%20PA%20Courier%201929-1930%20-%200453.pdf \"Bojangles to be starred with Adelaide Hall\"], ''Pittsburgh Courier'', 4 January 1930, p. 1. Retrieved 29 December 2014.</ref> True to the speculation, in 1930, Hall and [[Bill \"Bojangles\" Robinson]] starred together twice at New York's [[Palace Theatre (Broadway)|Palace Theatre]] on Broadway (in February and in August). Both appearances were for a weeks engagement.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1112010982.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+22%2C+1930&author=CHAPPIE+GARDNER&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=16&desc=White+Press+Acclaims+Adelaide+Hall+As+Packed+House+Gives+Her+Great+Ovation \"White Press Acclaims Adelaide Hall As Packed House Gives Her Great Ovation\"], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 22 February 1930.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=DVsKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA524&lpg=PA524&dq=palace+theatre+new+york+adelaide+hall&source=bl&ots=0g9xVMEZH_&sig=JxMyVbtf7kXk7nXBCUPUEmGGUDQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=P3iRVIj0MbCN7AbyzYHYDw&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=palace%20theatre%20new%20york%20adelaide%20hall&f=false Bill Robinson and Adelaide Hall Palace Theatre performance review] printed in ''Billboard'' magazine, 23 August 1930, and reproduced in ''Blacks in Blackface: A Sourcebook on Early Black Musical Shows'' by Henry T. Sampson, chapter 5, p. 524. Retrieved 17 December 2014.</ref> During her February appearance, which was Hall's first ever appearance at the [[Palace Theatre (Broadway)|Palace Theatre]], she received a roaring welcome in front of a capacity house and took six bows at the end of her performance. It was also noted in several newspapers that [[Lew Leslie]] had tried everything in his capacity bar from erecting a 'Rock of Gibraltar' to prevent Hall from appearing at any venue without his consent since she quit ''Blackbirds''. Having failed, Leslie did however manage to put a temporary restraint on her using any of the songs from ''Blackbirds'' in her show.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19300215&id=PWBGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kOUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5190,2225065 \"Adelaide Hall Gets hand in Vaudeville Debut\" \u2014 \"Former Star of Blackbirds Scores Heavily in Opening at Palace, N.Y.\"], ''The Afro American'', Baltimore, newspaper, p. 9, 15 February 1930. Retrieved 29 December 2014.</ref>\nSo successful was Hall's collaboration with Bojangles that in October 1930 the pair were teamed up together again, this time by Marty Forkins (Bojangles' manager) to star in the Broadway musical ''Brown Buddies.''<ref>Bernard L. Peterson, [https://archive.org/details/centuryofmusical0000pete/page/59 ''Brown Buddies'' article in ''A Century of Musicals in Black and White]: An Encyclopedia of Musical Stage Works by, about or Involving African Americans'', Westport, CT: Greenwood Publishing, 1993, pp. 59\u201360.</ref> The musical opened on Broadway at the [[Liberty Theatre (New York City)|Liberty Theatre]]<ref name=\"performingartsarchive.com\"/> where it ran for four months before commencing a road tour of the States.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19300927&id=IComAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5_0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4409,1348517 \"Dancing in 'Brown Buddies'\"], ''The Afro-American'', 27 September 1930.</ref><ref name=Playbill>[http://www.playbillvault.com/Show/Detail/6569/Brown-Buddies ''Brown Buddies'' playbill], Playbill Vault.</ref> Dubbed by the press as \"a musical comedy in sepia\", the core of the music was composed by Millard Thomas but also featured songs by [[Shelton Brooks]], Ned Reed, [[Porter Grainger]], [[J. C. Johnson]], J. Rosamund Johnson, George A. Little, Arthur Sizemore and Edward G. Nelson. After an out-of-town try-out, the musical opened on 7 October at the [[Liberty Theatre]], New York, where it ran a fairly solid run of 111 performances until 10 January 1931.<ref name=Playbill />\n\n===1931\u20131932: World concert tour===\nIn 1931, Hall embarked on a world concert tour that visited two continents (America and Europe). The tour was estimated to have performed to more than one million people. During the tour, she appeared four times at New York's [[Palace Theatre (Broadway)|Palace Theatre]].<ref>Williams, [http://www.bloomsbury.com/us/underneath-a-harlem-moon-9780826458933/''Underneath a Harlem Moon''], pp. 389, 390 and 395. Hall appears four times during her 1931/1932 world tour: February (with [[Noble Sissle]]), April, July and November.</ref> She was accompanied on stage by two pianists who played white grand pianos. It was during this tour that Hall discovered and employed the blind pianist [[Art Tatum]], whom she brought back to New York with her at the end of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/programs/jazzprofiles/archive/tatum.html|title=NPR's Jazz Profiles: Art Tatum|author=John Murph|website=Npr.org}}</ref><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/jazz/biography/artist_id_tatum_art.htm Art Tatum biography], PBS.</ref><ref>Bret Primack, [http://jazztimes.com/articles/21296-art-tatum-no-greater-art \"Art Tatum: No Greater Art Talkin' Tatum with Hank Jones, Billy Taylor, Dick Hyman, Adam Makowicz\"], ''JazzTimes'', January/February 1998.</ref> In August 1932, Hall recorded \"Strange as It Seems\", \"[[I'll Never Be the Same]]\", \"This Time It's Love\" and \"You Gave Me Everything but Love\" using Art Tatum as one of her pianists on the recordings.<ref>{{YouTube|zMK4VVKWgs8|\"Adelaide Hall \u2013 You Gave Me Everything But Love (1932)}}.</ref><ref>[http://handfulofkeys.wordpress.com/2011/07/17/more-than-a-handful-the-incomparable-art-tatum/ \"More Than a Handful \u2013 The Incomparable Art Tatum\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505221739/http://handfulofkeys.wordpress.com/2011/07/17/more-than-a-handful-the-incomparable-art-tatum/ |date=5 May 2014 }}, 17 July 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/art-tatum-jazz-pianist-born Art Tatum biography], African American Registry.</ref> Riverside Theatre, Milwaukee, 25 January 1932, review in ''[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]]'' of Hall's performance:\n\n<blockquote>Adelaide Hall, attractive young colored singer, dominates a vaudeville of staggering proportions. Miss Hall has the sort of \"blues\" voice that gets you and she has a fine dramatic sense. Her interpretation of \"River Stay Away From My Door,\" is strikingly good. And her gowns are lovely.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19320125&id=TlBQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6Q0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6679,4293192&hl=en Riverside Theatre \u2013 \"A Woman Commands\" \u2013 cinema and vaudeville review], ''The Milwaukee Sentinel'', 25 January 1932, p. 6.</ref></blockquote>\n\n===1932\u20131933: Larchmont, Westchester County, racist incident===\nIn the fall of 1932, upon her return to New York, Hall and her husband purchased the lease on an exclusive freehold residential estate in the [[Larchmont, New York|Village of Larchmont]] in the New York suburb of [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]]. As news of her arrival in Larchmont leaked into the local media she began to encounter racial opposition from her white upper-middle-class neighbors, who threatened court action to have Hall evicted. After her home was broken into and an attempt was made to set it alight, news of the attack hit national newspaper headlines. Receiving hundreds of letters of support from the American public imploring her to stick it out, Hall stood her ground and in a press statement she issued insisted that she was a true American citizen as her ancestry could be traced back to the [[Shinnecock Indian Nation|Shinnecock Indian tribe]] of [[Long Island]]<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19320827&id=y0xGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=f-UMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2002,7329768 \"Adelaide Hall twits white neighbours on their ancestry\"], ''The Afro-American'', 27 August 1932.</ref> and as such she had every right to reside where she wished.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19350803&id=8wInAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MQMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=5639,6701658 \"Why can\u2019t the stars live where they please?\"] ''The Afro-American'', 3 August 1935.</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19460709&id=4cMlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4fQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1036,3017341 \"Adelaide Hall interview \u2013 Why I Moved to London\"], ''Baltimore Afro-American'', 9 July 1946.</ref>\n\n===1933: Harlem Opera House, New York===\nFor one week commencing Saturday 14 January 1933, Hall returned to New York to appear in a music revue produced by [[Leonard Harper (producer)|Leonard Harper]] at the [[Harlem Opera House]]. A journalist from the ''[[Pittsburgh Courier]]'' newspaper who published under the initials T.Y. wrote in his review of Hall's performance that \"she was excellent\" and that he was so thrilled to be at the show he totally forgot to jot down on his notepad the title of the songs Hall performed. He did however apologise for this mishap. He also mentioned that Hall was accompanied on stage by a guitar \"troubadour\" and a blind pianist (referring to [[Art Tatum]]) who, he declared, \"can really play\".<ref>[http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%2023/Pittsburgh%20PA%20Courier/Pittsburgh%20PA%20Courier%201933/Pittsburgh%20PA%20Courier%201933%20-%200053.pdf 'New York's First Nighter' Adelaide Hall returns to Harlem], ''Pittsburgh Courier'', Saturday, 21 January 1933, p. 6, second section. Retrieved 1 February 2015.</ref>\n\n===1933: American concert tour===\n{{quote|ADELAIDE HALL TO TOUR THE COAST|''[[Pittsburgh Courier]]'' headline, 22 July 1933}} Hall's itinerary included all the principal cities and lasted 30 weeks<ref>Chappy Gardner, [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1114311312.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Jul+22%2C+1933&author=CHAPPY+GARDNER&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=A6&desc=ADELAIDE+HALL+TO+TOUR+THE+COAST \"ADELAIDE HALL TO TOUR THE COAST\"], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 22 July 1933.</ref>\n\n===World Fair City, Chicago, 1933===\n{{quote|Miss Adelaide Hall Captures The World Fair City and They Like It|''[[Pittsburgh Courier]]'', 19 August 1933:}}\n\n    'Miss Adelaide Hall, the darling girl with the guitar and the mellifluent voice, again stole into the callous hearts of an analytical public at the Regal theater last week. She charmed them with her voice, her poise and beauty. She has a style of singing '[[Stormy Weather (song)|Stormy Weather]]' all her own. Chicago belonged to Adelaide for one whole week. And her majesty feigned supreme. ''Pittsburgh Courier'',' 19 August 1933, [[Jules Bledsoe]].<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1109711212.html?}}FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+19%2C+1933&author=EARL+J+MORRIS&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=A6&desc=State+Street%2C+Chicago \"State Street, Chicago \u2013 Miss Adelaide Hall Captures The World Fair City and They Like It\"], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 19 August 1933.</ref>\n\nOn 19 August 1933, the fifth annual [[Bud Billiken Parade and Picnic]] took place during the prestigious [[Century of Progress|Chicago World Fair]]. African Americans came out in droves to support the event held by the ''[[Chicago Defender]]'' local newspaper. The ''Chicago Defender'' had named the event after a weekly column in its children's section written by [[Willard Motley]]. Billiken became a symbol of pride, happiness and hope for African-American youth. After the famous parade (the largest to date) a huge free picnic event was held in [[Washington Park (Chicago park)|Washington Park]] that included games, music, entertainment, dancing and ice cream. Performing in concert at the event in front of an estimated 50,000 people was the parade's guest of honour Adelaide Hall. Also appearing at the event were [[Cab Calloway]], [[Earl Hines]] and The Sioux Tribe of Native Americans.<ref>Cheryl Ganz, [https://books.google.com/books?id=GYXD8t4DDoIC&pg=PT163&dq=adelaide+hall+chicago&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tZdpU5vLI8a_ObH0gcgM&ved=0CGAQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=adelaide%20hall%20chicago&f=false ''The 1933 Chicago World's Fair \u2013 Century of Progress''], University of Illinois Press, 6 January 2012 ({{ISBN|0252078527}}). Adelaide Hall at the Billiken parade and Picnic reference on p. 115.</ref>\n\n===''Stormy Weather Revue'', 1933===\n''Stormy Weather Revue'' starring Adelaide Hall, New York, 29 November 1933. \"Although crippled from a fall into a manhole while appearing in Boston the week previous to her New York engagement, Adelaide Hall, scintillating star of the ''Stormy Weather Revue'', limps across the stage ahead of an array of stars, which go far to label this revue, about the finest to grace the boards,\" review taken from The ''[[Pittsburgh Courier]]''.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1112325162.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Dec+2%2C+1933&author=MAURICE+DANCER&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=A6&desc=%27STORMY+WEATHER%27+REVUE+STARS+ADELAIDE+HALL \"'Stormy Weather' Revue stars Adelaide Hall\"], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 2 December 1933.</ref> In October 1933, for the first time in history the entire floor revue from Harlem's [[Cotton Club (New York City)|Cotton Club]] went on tour, playing theatres in principal cities across the U.S. [[Irving Mills]] organised the tour and Adelaide Hall headlined the cast. Other performers on the bill included the [[Mills Blue Rhythm Band]] and [[George Dewey Washington]]. The revue was originally called ''The Cotton Club Parade of 1933'' but for the road tour it was changed to the ''Stormy Weather Revue''. As the name implies, the show contained the hit song \"[[Stormy Weather (song)|Stormy Weather]]\" written by [[Harold Arlen]] and [[Ted Koehler]], which had been introduced by [[Ethel Waters]] earlier that year at the Cotton Club in the ''Cotton Club Parade of 1933''.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1532&dat=19330923&id=0KA9AAAAIBAJ&sjid=visMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4392,9375602 \"Adelaide Hall with Cotton Club revue\"], article in ''The Afro-American'', 23 September 1933, p. 18.</ref>\n\n===1934: Apollo Theater, Harlem, ''Chocolate Soldiers'' revue===\n''Chocolate Soldiers'' opens at the new [[Apollo Theater]], Harlem, starring Adelaide Hall Harlem, New York, 14 February 1934: ''Chocolate Soldiers'', a production featuring Adelaide Hall and the [[Sam Wooding]] Orchestra, opened at the [[Apollo Theater]] in Harlem. The show was produced by Clarence Robinson and garnered great attention and acclaim<ref>[http://tommytommitomme.tumblr.com/post/46303054372/clarencerobinson Article about producer Clarence Robinson] and his involvement with Harlem's Apollo Theater and the show ''Chocolate Soldiers'' starring Adelaide Hall.</ref> and helped establish the recently opened Apollo as Harlem's premier theatre.\n\n===''The Cotton Club Parade'', 1934===\nOn 23 March 1934, Hall opened at Harlem's [[Cotton Club]] in ''The Cotton Club Parade'' 24th Edition.<ref>Steven Suskin, [https://books.google.com/books?id=_3mOZv6OaUIC&pg=PA147 \"Cotton Club Parade, 1934\"], in ''Show Tunes: The Songs, Shows, and Careers of Broadway's Major Composers'', Oxford University Press, 2010, p. 147. Retrieved 14 September 2014.</ref> It was the largest grossing show ever staged there.<ref>{{YouTube|fjI1tbAXO2w|\"Adelaide Hall talks about 1920s Harlem and Creole Love Call\"}}.</ref><ref>Steven Watson, [http://xroads.virginia.edu/~ug97/blues/watson.html \"The Harlem Renaissance\".]</ref><ref>Kennet B. Hilliard, [http://www.yale.edu/ynhti/curriculum/units/1989/1/89.01.05.x.html \"The Impact of the Music of the Harlem Renaissance on Society\"]. Yale-New Haven Teachers Institute.</ref> The show ran for six months at the Cotton Club. In the show Hall introduced the songs \"[[Ill Wind (Arlen-Koehler song)|Ill Wind]]\"<ref>[http://www.jazzstandards.com/compositions-2/illwind.htm \"Ill Wind\"] at JazzStandards.com</ref> and \"Primitive Prima Donna\", which [[Harold Arlen]] and [[Ted Koehler]] wrote especially for her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jass.com/cotton1934.html|title=Jass.com: Cotton Club Revues 1934|author=Tom Morgan|work=jass.com|access-date=9 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818002251/http://jass.com/cotton1934.html|archive-date=18 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haroldarlen.com/bio-4.html|title=Harold Arlen \u2013 Biography \u2013 The Cotton Club Years|work=haroldarlen.com}}</ref><ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1110765322.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+18%2C+1934&author=MAURICE+DANCER&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=A8&desc=HARLEM+NIGHT+CLUBS+BRILLIANT+AND+LIVELY \"Harlem Night Clubs Brilliant and Lively \u2013 Adelaide Hall, Gladys Bentley Featured Stars], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 18 August 1934.</ref> It was during Hall's rendition of \"[[Ill Wind (Arlen-Koehler song)|Ill Wind]]\" that nitrogen smoke was used to cover the floor of the stage. It was the first time such an effect had ever been used on a stage and caused a sensation.<ref name=Voce /> So successful was the show, the entire production went on a roadtour playing in theatre's across America.\n[[File:Adelaide Hall - Cotton Club Revue of 1934, Loew's Metropolitan Theater, Brooklyn, 6 September 1934, (Advertisment).jpg|thumb|left|Adelaide Hall starring in the Cotton Club Revue of 1934 at the Loew's Metropolitan Theater, Brooklyn, commencing on 7 September 1934 (advertisement).]]\n\n===1935: North and South American concert tour===\nDuring 1935, Hall performed another coast-to-coast American/Canadian concert tour that took in the South. Prior to the tour commencing she gave an interview (during her visit to [[Dixie]]), conducted by the journalist George Tyler that was published on 16 March 1935 in ''The Afro-American'' newspaper. In the interview Hall gives a rare insight into her life and her home in the [[Larchmont, New York|Village of Larchmont]], disclosing how dramatically her circumstances had changed since her humble upbringing in Harlem.\n\n{{quote|\"Much has been said and published too, about the magnificent residence of Miss Hall,\" says George, \"but my interest was in what transpires behind the portals of this mansion when the singer is at home.\"\n\n\"I have a sun parlour,\" said Adelaide, \"in which I take a keen delight. Here, while enjoying the rays of the sun, I crochet and listen to the radio. A great deal of my time off the stage I spend painting or working in my garden. My favorite radio artists are [[Mildred Bailey]], [[Willard Robison]] and his Deep River Orchestra, and the [[Southernaires]]. My stage favorites include [[Bill Robinson]], [[Ethel Waters]] and [[Ada Brown]]. While at home I do very little cooking; in fact, there are servants to take care of these details. The cook's biggest job is to prepare broiled chicken, as that is one of my favorite dishes.\"}}\n\nTyler adds that the singing star owns and drives her car, roller skates, swims, plays tennis and enjoys horseback riding.\n\n<blockquote>\"When I retire from public life I shall resume my career as a modiste,\" confided Miss Hall. \"As a kid I longed for a stage career, and my first step towards this was to run away from school to try my luck behind the footlights. I was apprehended and sent back to school to continue my training as a modiste. Today, I am proud that I am more than an actress\".</blockquote>\n\nTyler continues by asking about her forthcoming American and Canadian concert tour, which will take her deep into the South: \"What do you think of such a tour, under the conditions that exist in the South?\" Hall replied:\n\n<blockquote>My experience of a couple of years ago while on a coast-to-coast tour should serve me well.  Being a member of the oppressed race, I think I will be able to accustom myself to conditions, as they exist. However, there are many details I would rather not go into.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19350316&id=4AInAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MQMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1945,2349820 \"Adelaide Hall: A Harlem Song-Bird Will Invade Dixie\"], \"Looking at the Stars with Ralph Matthews\", ''The Afro-American'', week of 16 March 1935, p. 8. Retrieved 25 August 2014.</ref></blockquote>\n\n===European career, 1935\u20131938===\nHall arrived in Paris, France in the fall of 1935<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/pittsburghcourier/access/1114442962.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+30%2C+1935&author=&pub=The+Pittsburgh+Courier+(1911-1950)&edition=&startpage=A7&desc=Adelaide+Hall+And+Meeres+%26+Meeres+Off+For+London \"Adelaide Hall And Meeres & Meeres Off For London\"], ''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 30 November 1935.</ref> and remained living there until 1938. Her husband Bert opened a nightclub for her in Paris, situated at 73 rue Pigalle in [[Montmartre]], called ''La Grosse Pomme'' where she frequently entertained.<ref>[http://midniteinparis.tumblr.com/post/9935090286/performer-adelaide-hall-and-her-husband-manager \"Performer Adelaide Hall and her husband/manager, Bert Hicks, owned a nightclub in Montmartre called La Grosse Pomme...\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005003326/http://midniteinparis.tumblr.com/post/9935090286/performer-adelaide-hall-and-her-husband-manager |date=5 October 2013 }}, Midnight in Paris.</ref><ref>[http://www.paulvernonchester.com/DjangoHaunts.htm \"Django's Haunts\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021122637/http://www.paulvernonchester.com/DjangoHaunts.htm |date=21 October 2014 }}, Paul Vernon Chester.</ref> \"It (the club) held about two hundred people. I made this dramatic entrance coming down a spiral staircase from the attic. Nobody knew that all the boxes of wine and tinned food were stored up there with me. I came down the stairs in the most gorgeous costumes you'll ever see, floating in feathers and plumes,\" recalled Adelaide during an interview.<ref name=Voce />\n\nThe [[Quintette du Hot Club de France]] featuring [[Django Reinhardt]] and [[Stephane Grappelli]] were one of the house bands at the club. At the beginning of 1936, Hall starred in the ''Black and White Revue''. The show of 50 performers opened in Paris, France and in February the production travelled to Switzerland for a tour. The revue was produced by [[Ralph Clayton]], staged by Arthur Bradley and choreographed by ballet master Albert Gaubier who had danced under the direction of [[Serge Diaghilev]] in the Russian company ''[[Ballets Russes]]''.<ref>[https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=da&u=http://www.danskefilm.dk/skuespiller/10555.html&prev=search Albert Gaubier danced under the direction of Serge Diaghilev]. Albert Gaubier biography, retrieved 17 December 2014.</ref> The orchestra that travelled with the production was under the direction of [[Henry Crowder]].<ref>Henry Crowder biography: [http://abar.net/crowder.htm Allardyce Barnett.]</ref> During the August 1936 Olympic games held in Berlin, Germany, Adelaide appeared at Berlin's Rex Theatre singing jazz.<ref>''Just Remember This'' by Colin Bratkovich, published Xlibris {{ISBN|1483645185}} (2014) p. 150. Retrieved 17 August 2018.</ref> Her performance is notable as she contravened [[Adolf Hitler]]'s ban on jazz music being played.\n\nIn 1937, Hall choreographed her own take on the famous French dance the [[Can-can]]; she called it the Canned Apple and would perform it at her Montmartre nightclub ''La Grosse Pomme''.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19371225&id=gxomAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mP0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=3591,4341116 \"Adelaide Hall shows Paris Canned Apple\"], ''The Afro-American'', 25 December 1937.</ref> Hall is also credited with introducing the Truckin' dance craze to the Parisians.<ref>Ida Peters, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19931106&id=mJ8lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7fQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1675,3403220 \"What's Happening | Adelaide Hall introduced Truckin' to Paris\"], ''Baltimore Afro-American'', 6 November 1993.</ref> During her residence in Europe, Hall sang with several orchestras, including those of [[Willie Lewis]]<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/song/say-youre-mine-mt0005764420 Adelaide Hall and Willie Lewis and his Entertainers recording of \"Say You're Mine\"], AllMusic.</ref> and [[Ray Ventura]] and in 1937 (while on a trip to [[Copenhagen]]) she recorded four songs with [[Kai Ewans]] and his Orchestra for the Tono record label.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/KaiEwansOrchVadelaideHall-WhereOrWhen1937 Kai Ewans Orchestra] with Adelaide Hall singing \"Where or When\".</ref> On 13 May 1938, [[BBC Radio]] broadcast ''Over to Paris'', an hour-long programme direct from a Paris studio that highlighted a variety of famous Parisian artists of radio, cabaret and the music hall. The show included performances from Adelaide Hall and [[Mistinguett]], who were accompanied by two orchestras.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/1c39099f7c744903a3f314232db022d1|title=Over to Paris|date=13 May 1938|issue=762|pages=66|via=BBC Genome}}</ref>\n\n==Move to London, 1938==\n===British career, 1938\u20131993===\nAfter many years performing in the US and Europe, Hall went to the United Kingdom in 1938<ref>Douglass Hall, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4cMlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4fQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1036,3017341&dq=adelaide+hall&hl=en \"Why I Moved to London, How America's Peculiar Brand of Democracy Forced a Brooklyn Girl to Live in Europe\"], ''Baltimore Afro-American'', 9 July 1946, p. 5 (with a large photograph of Adelaide Hall).</ref> to take a starring role in a stage-adapted musical version of [[Edgar Wallace]]'s ''The Sun Never Sets'' at the [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0212704/otherworks ''The Sun Never Sets'' cast list], IMDb.</ref><ref name=\"screenonline1\">[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/580633/index.html \"Hall, Adelaide (1901\u20131993), Actor, Singer\"], BFI ScreenOnline.</ref> She was so successful and became so popular with British audiences she stayed and made her home there becoming one of the most popular singers and entertainers of the time. Hall lived in London from 1938 until her death.\n\nOn 28 August 1938, Hall recorded \"[[I Can't Give You Anything But Love]]\" and \"[[That Old Feeling (song)|That Old Feeling]]\"<ref>{{YouTube|JZrKKs-gUds|\"That Old Feeling\" sung by Adelaide Hall with Fats Waller playing the organ}}.</ref> at London's [[Abbey Road Studios]], with [[Fats Waller]] accompanying her on the organ. The recordings were released on HMV Records OEA6391. On 10 September 1938, she appeared in ''Broadcast To America'' with Waller at London's [[St. George's Hall, London|St George's Hall]] in a live transatlantic radio broadcast.<ref name=WallerBroadcasts>Ken Dryden, [http://www.allaboutjazz.com/fats-waller-on-the-air-1938-broadcasts-fats-waller-tai-ping-review-by-ken-dryden.php#.VBWPlUu4mlI \"Fats Waller: Fats Waller on the Air 1938 Broadcasts (2009)\"], including duets with Adelaide Hall. AllAboutJazz, 7 April 2010. Retrieved 14 September 2014.</ref><ref>[http://kindofjazzbloglibrary.blogspot.co.uk/2012/11/13-fats-waller-on-air-sessions-1938.html ''Broadcast To America''] released on CD in 2012.</ref>\n\nOn 25 February 1939, [[BBC TV]] broadcast ''Harlem in Mayfair'' from Adelaide Hall's London nightclub, the Old Florida Club. The cabaret show starred Hall; also on the bill were Esther and Louise, Eddie Lewis, and [[Fela Sowande]] with his Negro Choir and Orchestra.<ref name=\"Don't Call Them Crooners\">[[Leonard Feather]], [http://www.radiotimesarchive.co.uk/pdf/RT-TV-1939.pdf \"Don't Call Them Crooners: 4 \u2013 Adelaide Hall\" (interview)], ''Radio Times'', 17 February 1939, p. 15. Includes a photograph of Hall and mentions performers with whom she had recorded and performed, including Rudy Vallee.</ref><ref>[http://www.radiotimesarchive.co.uk/pdf/RT-TV-1939.pdf \"Harlem in Mayfair\"], BBC TV listings, ''Radio Times'', Saturday, 25 February 1939.</ref> On 20 May 1939, BBC TV broadcast the cabaret show ''Dark Sophistication'', starring Hall performing at the Old Florida Club.<ref>[http://www.radiotimesarchive.co.uk/pdf/RT-TV-1939.pdf BBC TV listings], ''Radio Times'', Saturday, 20 May 1939.</ref> On 26 August 1939, Hall took part in the BBC TV production ''Kentucky Minstrels'', which was transmitted live from the 2500-seat RadiOlympia Theatre in London.<ref>[http://www.radiotimesarchive.co.uk/pdf/RT-TV-1939.pdf BBC TV listings], ''Radio Times'', 18 August 1939, p. 17.</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3616006/ \"The Kentucky Minstrels\"], IMBD.</ref> \n[[File:Radiolympia Thursday 31 August 1939 Kentucky Minstrels show starring Adelaide Hall.jpg|thumb|left|Radiolympia, Thursday 31 August 1939, ''Kentucky Minstrels'' show starring Adelaide Hall]] \nOn Friday, 1 September 1939, Hall was scheduled to appear that evening at 9:00 pm in a live BBC TV broadcast titled ''Variety'' recorded direct from the RadiOlympia Theatre.<ref>[http://uktvschedules.editthis.info/wiki/01_September_1939 BBC TV programme listings] for 1 September 1939.</ref><ref>[http://www.radiotimesarchive.co.uk/pdf/RT-TV-1939.pdf ''Radio Times''], issue, 25 August 1939, p. 21.</ref> Other performers on the bill included [[H. Vernon Watson|Nosmo King]], The Gordon RadiOlympia Girls, Hubert Murray and Mooney, and Bobby Howell and his Band. However, with war looming, the BBC were instructed by the government to shut down broadcasting and at 12:35 the service went off the air for seven years. It appears that the show ''Variety'' never took place at RadiOlympia; ''The Times'' newspaper for the following day (2 September) noted in their section 'News in Brief' that \"RadiOlympia closed at 12:30 yesterday\", presumably another result of the country being placed on a war footing.<ref>Russ J. Graham, [http://www.transdiffusion.org/tv/baird/tvoff \"The edit that rewrote history] \u2013 What really did happen that day in 1939, when the BBC Television Service closed down 'for the duration of the conflict'?\" Transdiffusion Broadcasting System, 31 October 2005.</ref> Unexpectedly, the show ''Variety'' became one of the first British theatrical casualties of [[World War II]] and part of the mystery surrounding \"what really happened at the BBC on 1 September 1939?\" Also during 1939, Hall became a featured vocalist with [[Joe Loss]] & His Band<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/joe-loss-mn0000140296 Joe Loss biography], in which Adelaide Hall is mentioned as being a featured vocalist in his band: \"The new-featured vocalist in Joe Loss's broadcasts is one of America's veterans of jazz singing, her career dating back to the first big Negro revue, ''Shuffle Along'', produced on Broadway in 1921.\"</ref> and through 1939 to 1941, Hall headlined the popular BBC Radio variety show ''Piccadixie''.<ref>[http://www.britishonlinearchives.co.uk/page.php?did=248-r9-11-05&pageno=6&date_option=equal&textonly=yes PROGRAMME FOR THE FORCES HOME SERVICE]. \"PIccadixie\" (''Variety'') 12.00 midnight radio show. General Listening Barometer, Week 28, Sunday, 6 July 1943. Subject to the limitations of sampling, the figures below show the percentage of the whole adult population of Great Britain who listened to each item.</ref> She also toured the UK extensively during these years headlining the ''Piccadixie British Tour'' supported by comedian [[Oliver Wakefield]] and pianist [[George Elrick]].<ref>A poster advertising ''Piccadixie'' with the performers: Adelaide Hall (singer), Oliver Wakefield (comedian), [[George Elrick]] (musician) appearing at the New Empress Theatre, [[Brixton]], London, 8 December 1941, can be found at [https://collections.vam.ac.uk the V&A in their collection.]</ref>\n[[File:Adelaide Hall starring in Piccadixie at the Finsbury Park Empire, London, 28 July 1941.jpg|thumb|left|Adelaide Hall starring in ''Piccadixie'' at the Finsbury Park Empire, London, 28 July 1941 (detail from original programme)]]\nDuring WWII, Hall entertained the troops in Europe for the USO ([[United Service Organizations]] Inc.)<ref>Article by Ida Peters [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19931106&id=mJ8lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7fQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1675,3 (''Baltimore Afro-American'', 13 November 1993, p. B7)] mentions that Adelaide Hall entertained the troops in Europe for the USO.</ref> and the British equivalent ENSA ([[Entertainments National Service Association]]) in which she served as a captain. Her uniform was made by Madam Adele of Grosvenor Street in Mayfair, London.<ref>Angie Macdonald, [http://dulwichonview.org.uk/2008/04/11/keep-smiling-through/ \"Keep Smiling Through\"], Dulwich Online, 11 April 2008. Review of the \"Keep Smiling Through\" exhibition that features recollections of Adelaide Hall entertaining the troops during WWII.</ref> On 17 October 1939, the first large-scale variety concert organized by [[ENSA]] was staged at [[RAF Hendon]] in north London. Starring on the bill was Adelaide Hall, The [[Western Brothers]] and [[Mantovani]] and his Orchestra.<ref>[https://wargaming.com/en/news/entertaining_allied_troops/ \"Entertaining Allied Troops in WWII\"], Wargaming.net. Retrieved 17 August 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-scene-at-an-raf-variety-concert-at-adelaide-hall-showing-a-singer-20612792.html A scene at an unspecified RAF Variety concert during WWII showing Adelaide Hall performing the song \"Hang Out Your Washing On The Siegfried Line\"]. Alamy Photo Archive.</ref>\nAdelaide recalled in vivid detail the challenges she faced during WWII while entertaining the troops across Europe and in the UK, some of whom were wounded;<ref>[https://www.ourwarwickshire.org.uk/content/article/bringing-jazz-warwickshires-wounded-adelaide-halls-wartime-performances \"Bringing Jazz To Warwickshire\u2019s Wounded: Adelaide Hall\u2019s Wartime Performances\"], with photo \"Adelaide Hall singing to wounded soldiers at the Rotary Club at Myton Hamlet, Leamington Spa Courier, 28 July 1944\". ''Our Warwickshire''.</ref> 'Sometimes I had to sing without music, but it was a challenge, and so rewarding to get all the people to sing with me.' At one London performance Hall gave at Lewisham Hippodrome theatre during the week of 20 August 1940, the Luftwaffe attacked overhead dropping bombs and, 'even though we could hear bombs exploding outside the theatre, we carried on ... I had sung 54 songs until the all-clear sounded at 3:45&nbsp;a.m. in the morning!\u2019<ref name=WW2>Stephen Bourne, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/05/a3857105.shtml \"When Adelaide Hall Went to War\"], WW2 People's War, BBC Archive.\n</ref> Hall's 54 encores are believed to be a world record for the amount of encores sung by one artist on stage.<ref>Mel Wright, [http://www.tonyellis.net/melwright/images/AHall.jpg \"Lady stays to sing away the wartime blues\" | \"Lewisham Hippodrome \u2018Youth Takes A Bow\u2019 20 August 1940 for a week\"], via Tonyellis.net.</ref><ref>Adelaide Hall sang 54 encores until the all-clear sounded at 3:45 a.m. Stephen Bourne, [https://www.londonnewsonline.co.uk/south-london-memories-jazz-singer-adelaide-hall-sang-as-bombs-fell/ \"South London Memories: Jazz singer Adelaide Hall sang as bombs fell\"], ''South London Press and Mercury'', 3 July 2018.</ref> Hall also claimed to be one of the first entertainers to enter [[Germany]] before the war had officially ended. She travelled with the troops as they advanced towards [[Berlin]] dismissing the dangers such bravery entailed.<ref name=WW2 />\n\nHall's career was almost an uninterrupted success. She made more than 70 records for [[Decca Records|Decca]],<ref>[http://www.jazzdisco.org/prestige-records/discography-1933-1948/ Prestige Records] Discography: 1933\u20131948.</ref> had her own BBC Radio series, ''Wrapped in Velvet''<ref>\"During WWII, she hosted a radio show in London called Wrapped in Velvet\"; extract from June Sochen, [https://archive.org/details/frommaetomadonna0000soch/page/38 ''From Mae to Madonna: Women Entertainers in Twentieth-century America''], p. 38. {{ISBN|9780813191997}}.</ref><ref>David Hinkley, \"Scat-Singing Pioneer Adelaide Hall Never Really Went Out of Style\", ''New York Daily News'' (reprinted by the Knight-Ridder/Tribune News Service, 19 November 1993, 1119K3115.</ref> (making her the first black artist to have a long-term contract with the BBC), and appeared on the stage, in films, and in nightclubs (of which she owned her own in New York, London and Paris). In the 1940s, and especially during World War II, she was hugely popular with civilian and [[Entertainments National Service Association]] (ENSA) audiences<ref>Stephen Bourne, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/05/a3857105.shtml \"When Adelaide Hall Went to War\"], WW2 People's War, BBC.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/home-front-songs-from-world/id360288110|title=\"Home Front \u2013 Songs From World War II\".|website=Itunes.apple.com}}</ref> and became one of Britain's highest paid entertainers. Her London nightclub The Old Florida Club owned by Hall and her husband was destroyed by a landmine during an air raid in 1939.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elvirabarney.wordpress.com/tag/adelaide-hall/|title=Adelaide Hall \u2013 Cocktails With Elvira|website=Wordpress.com}}</ref> Her husband Bert was in the club's cellar when the landmine exploded but he survived the attack. Hall has a cameo appearance as a singer in the 1940 [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning movie ''[[The Thief of Bagdad (1940 film)|The Thief of Bagdad]]'' (directed by [[Michael Powell]] (and others) and produced by [[Alexander Korda]]) in which she sings ''Lullaby of the Princess'' written by [[Mikl\u00f3s R\u00f3zsa]].<ref name=\"screenonline1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0355263/|title=Adelaide Hall|work=IMDb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0033152/fullcredits|title=The Thief of Bagdad (1940) |website=IMDb.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.powell-pressburger.org/Reviews/40_Thief/Thief06.html Mikl\u00f3s R\u00f3zsa interview] explaining how he came to write the score for ''The Thief of Bagdad''.</ref> In 1943, Hall featured in an ENSA radio show broadcast by the BBC entitled ''Spotlight on the Stars'' during which she was accompanied by the BBC Variety Orchestra. During the show she mentions how she had just returned home from a tour.<ref>An original radio recording \u2013 ENSA Presents Spotlight on the Stars \u2013 Adelaide Hall with the BBC Variety Orchestra \u2013 broadcast in 1943: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LiB8MfyETKU YouTube.]</ref> On 20 May 1940, Hall's recording of \"Careless\" debuted in the British charts at number 30, where it remained for two consecutive weeks. In the August 1940 issue of ''[[Vogue (British magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine (British edition), a photograph of Hall appears on the 'Spotlight' page compiled by the features editor [[Lesley Blanch]] under the caption: \"Adelaide Hall and her husband run the Florida. His show, her songs, our fun.\"<ref>[http://www.vogue.co.uk/magazine/archive/issue/1940/August ''Vogue'' magazine (British issue)], August 1940. Retrieved 13 September 2014.</ref> On 6 June 1945, Hall's recording of \"There Goes That Song Again\" entered the BBC British charts at number 15.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/58/a3090458.shtml \"6 June 1944 BBC Record Chart\"], WW2 People's War, BBC.</ref>\n\nHall appears in the earliest post-war BBC [[telerecording]]: a live recording of her performance at RadiOlympia Theatre on 7 October 1947. The footage was filmed on the 'Cafe Continental' stage set at the theatre for a [[BBC TV]] show titled ''[[Variety in Sepia]]''.<ref>Getty Images:[http://www.gettyimages.in/detail/nieuwsfoto's/the-first-radiolympia-since-the-war-30-september-1947-the-nieuwsfotos/102730194 A view of the 'Cafe Continental' stage set] in the television studio at RadiOlympia Theatre, London, September 1947.</ref> Hall sings \"[[Chi-Baba, Chi-Baba (My Bambino Go to Sleep)]]\" and \"[[I Can't Give You Anything But Love]]\" and accompanies herself on ukulele and dancing. When the show was broadcast on BBC TV it was 60 minutes in length and included performances from [[Winifred Atwell]], [[Evelyn Dove]], [[Cyril Blake]] and his Calypso Band, [[Edric Connor]] and [[Mable Lee]] and was produced by Eric Fawcett. The six-minute footage of Hall is all that survives of the show.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4177254/?ref_=ttfc_fc_tt \"Variety in Sepia (1947)\"] at IMDb.</ref> In 1948, Hall appeared in a British movie called ''A World is Turning''. The movie was intended to highlight the contribution of black men and women to British society at a time when they were struggling for visibility on the screens. Filming appears to have been halted due to the director's illness and only six reels of rushes remain, including scenes of Hall rehearsing songs such as \"[[Swing Low, Sweet Chariot]]\"<ref>{{YouTube|VgBqvqRsxSk|\"Adelaide Hall \u2013 'Swing Low, Sweet Chariot' (1948)\"}}.</ref> and \"[[The Gospel Train]]\"<ref>{{YouTube|1jlfpAb3Uc8 \"Adelaide Hall at the Nightingale Club, London (1948)\"}}.</ref> (a traditional African-American spiritual first published in 1872 as one of the songs of the [[Fisk Jubilee Singers]]). In 1949, Hall appeared on the BBC TV shows ''Rooftop Rendezvous'' and ''Caribbean Carnival''. Also in 1949, Adelaide recorded five spirituals accompanied by the pianist Kenneth Cantril.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondhandsongs.com/artist/33605+90211|title=Adelaide Hall and Kenneth Cantril |website=Secondhandsongs.com|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> The five songs chosen and released by London Records were \"[[Swing Low Sweet Chariot]]\", \"Bye and Bye\", \"[[Nobody Knows the Trouble I've Seen|Nobody Know De Trouble I\u2019ve Seen]]\", \"[[Sometimes I Feel Like a Motherless Child]]\", and \"[[Deep River (song)|Deep River]]\".\n\nIn 1951, Hall appeared as a guest in the music spot on the first ever British comedy series ''How Do You View'', starring [[Terry-Thomas]] and written by Sid Colin and Talbot Rothwell.<ref>[http://www.turnipnet.com/whirligig/tv/adults/other/british.htm \"British Programmes\"], Whirligig: \"''How Do You View''? (1951) was the first-ever comedy series on British television and starred [[Terry-Thomas]]: the show's musical spot was filled by guests such as [[Dickie Valentine]], [[Lita Roza]], Adelaide Hall and [[Jimmy Young (disc jockey)|Jimmy Young]].\"</ref> On 29 October 1951, Hall appeared on the bill of the [[Royal Variety Performance]] at the [[Victoria Palace Theatre]] in the presence of [[Elizabeth II|Princess Elizabeth]] and [[Princess Margaret]].<ref>[http://www.eabf.org.uk/royal-variety-performance/archive/1951 The Royal Variety Performance] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121224023809/http://www.eabf.org.uk/royal-variety-performance/archive/1951 |date=24 December 2012 }}, 29 October 1951, Victoria Palace Theatre, London.</ref> Alongside Trinidad-born US dancer Pearl Primus and the female members of her company, who also performed that year, Hall was the first black female artiste to ever take part in the Royal Variety Performance.<ref>[http://www.npg.org.uk/devotional/honours.html A mention of Adelaide Hall being the first black female artist to appear on the bill of the Royal Variety Performance] is included in this list of awards, honours and firsts for British black female artistes.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eabf.org.uk/|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121224023809/http://www.eabf.org.uk/royal-variety-performance/archive/1951|url-status=dead|title=Events & Business Functions &#124; EABF|archivedate=24 December 2012|website=Eabf.org.uk}}</ref> In the early 1950s, Hall and her husband Bert opened the Calypso Club in [[Regent Street]], London, and Royalty flocked there.<ref>[[Louis Lautier]], [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hfglAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bfUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1306,1697476&dq=adelaide+hall+afro&hl=en \"Capital Spotlight\"], ''Baltimore Afro-American'', 14 October 1952, p. 17.</ref> It was reported in the press that Princess Elizabeth was a frequent visitor and that Hall had taught the princess the [[Charleston (dance)|Charleston]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dEMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA66 ''Jet''], 15 May 1952, p. 66. Article about Adelaide Hall (includes a photograph) mentioning her Calypso Club in London and how she taught Princess Elizabeth to dance the Charleston.</ref>\n\nHall appeared in the 1951 London run of ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' playing the role of Hattie, singing [[Cole Porter]]'s \"[[Another Op'nin', Another Show]]\", and in the 1952 London musical ''Love From Judy''<ref name=Sommerlad>[http://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O86665/adelaide-hall-in-ilove-from-caricature-sommerlad-gilbert/ Caricature of Adelaide Hall in her role as Butterfly in ''Love From Judy''] drawn by Gilbert Sommerlad held in the V&A Collection Archive.</ref> playing the role of Butterfly, singing \"A Touch of Voodoo\", \"Kind to Animals\" and \"Ain't Gonna Marry\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guidetomusicaltheatre.com/shows_l/lovefrom_judy.htm|title=Love From Judy|work=guidetomusicaltheatre.com}}</ref> In 1956, she returned to London's West End in the play ''Someone to Talk To''.<ref name=NYTobit>Glenn Collins, [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/10/obituaries/adelaide-hall-92-international-star-of-cabaret.html \"Adelaide Hall, 92, International Star of Cabaret\"] (obituary, listing some of her stage performances), ''New York Times'', 10 November 1993.</ref> In 1957, at the request of [[Lena Horne]], Hall returned to America to appear with Horne in the musical ''[[Jamaica (musical)|Jamaica]]''. The world premiere of ''Jamaica'' took place in Philadelphia in September 1957<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=G-ElAAAAIBAJ&sjid=o_QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=713,4747063&dq=adelaide+hall+afro&hl=en \"Lena Horne and ''Jamaica'' in Philly world premiere\"] (with large photograph of Lena, Adelaide and Ricardo Montalban), ''Washington Afro-American'', 3 September 1957, p. 33.</ref> and transferred to Broadway on 31 October. In 1958, Hall was cast as one of the lead characters in [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]'s new musical ''[[Flower Drum Song]]''.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8zsmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=u_4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6535,2933764&dq=adelaide+hall&hl=en \"Adelaide Hall in new musical\"], ''Washington Afro-American'', 12 August 1958.</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 1960, Hall appeared on the BBC TV music show ''The Music Goes Round'' hosted by John Watt. The show was an NBA TV version of the radio show ''Songs from the Shows''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvpopdiaries.co.uk/1960.html|title=TV Pop Diaries 1960|work=tvpopdiaries.co.uk}}</ref> On 3 March 1965, Hall appeared on BBC2 television in ''Muses with Milligan'' with [[Spike Milligan]] and [[John Betjeman]] in a show devoted to poetry and jazz.<ref>{{YouTube|HK75L_vBaHs|\"Muses With Milligan \u2013 BBCtv 1965 \u2013 Restoration Split Screen Demo\"}}.</ref> In 1968, Hall appeared in ''Janie Jones'', a new American play written by Robert P. Hillier and directed by [[Peter Cotes]]. The cast included American actress [[Marlene Warfield]]. The play had its world premiere on 8 July at Manchester Opera House, where it ran for one week prior to its London West End opening on 15 July at the New Theatre (now the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]]).<ref name=NYTobit />\n\nBetween 1969 and 1970, Hall made two jazz recordings with [[Humphrey Lyttelton]]. This was followed by theatre tours and concert appearances; she sang at [[Duke Ellington]]'s memorial service at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]] in 1974.<ref>[https://www.shutterstock.com/editorial/image-editorial/adelaide-hall-and-cleo-laine-attend-memorial-service-for-duke-ellington-at-st-martininthefield-london-1779703a 12 June 1974]: Photograph of Adelaide Hall attending the Duke Ellington Memorial Concert at St Martin-in-the-field, London, accompanied by [[Cleo Laine]]. Shutterstock.</ref> On 4 January 1974, she appeared on the British TV shows ''Looks Familiar'' (as a panelist)<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/648214 ''Looks Familiar''] at BFI.</ref> and on ''What Is Jazz'', with [[Humphrey Lyttelton]].<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/615778 ''What Is Jazz?''] at BFI.</ref> On 15 June 1976, she appeared on British TV in ''It Don't Mean a Thing''.<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/697963?view=credit ''It Don't Mean a Thing'' credits], BFI.</ref> and in 1981 appeared on the [[Michael Parkinson]] BBC TV show ''Parkinson'' as a guest.<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/308966?view=credit ''Parkinson: 300'' credits], BFI.</ref> In July 1982, Hall appeared at a Gala concert held at [[St Paul's Cathedral]] in London to celebrate the sacred music of Duke Ellington. A live recording of the concert titled ''The Sacred Music of Duke Ellington'' was filmed for a [[Channel 4]] TV documentary. Artists also taking part included [[Tony Bennett]], [[Phyllis Hyman]], [[Jacques Loussier]], [[Alan Downey]], [[Wayne Sleep]], [[Ronnie Scott]], [[Stan Tracey]] and the New Swingle Singers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/119040?view=credit|title=The Sacred Music of Duke Ellington (1983)|publisher=BFI}}</ref> The concert was hosted by [[Rod Steiger]] and narrated by [[Douglas Fairbanks Jr]].<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/item/jots.200018968 ''The Sacred Music of Duke Ellington'' concert] at St Paul's Cathedral, London, 1982: Library of Congress details for the event.</ref>\n\nIn April 1980, Hall returned to the U.S. and from 1 to 24 May, she appeared in the cast of ''Black Broadway'' (a retrospective musical revue) at the [[The Town Hall (New York City)|Town Hall]] in New York. Among other artists appearingd in the show were [[Elisabeth Welch]], [[Gregory Hines]], [[Bobby Short]], [[Honi Coles]], [[Edith Wilson]], [[Nell Carter]] and John W. Bubbles of [[Buck and Bubbles]] fame. The show originally was staged at the [[Newport Jazz Festival]] on 24 June 1979, before it was re-assembled in 1980 and staged at the Town Hall.<ref>{{cite book|author=Bernard L. Peterson|title=A Century of Musicals in Black and White: An Encyclopedia of Musical Stage Works By, About, Or Involving African Americans|url=https://archive.org/details/centuryofmusical0000pete|url-access=registration|year=1993|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-26657-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/centuryofmusical0000pete/page/40 40]\u201341}}</ref> Following ''Black Broadway'', in June 1980, Hall took up temporary residence at Michael's Pub in New York and commenced a three-week engagement, performing three shows a night.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WOUCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA94 Listing for Michael's Pub], ''New York'' magazine, 2 June 1980, p. 94.</ref> Also in June 1980, she performed at the [[Playboy Jazz Festival]] held at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] in [[Los Angeles]]. Other artists on the bill included [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[St\u00e9phane Grappelli]], [[Mel Torm\u00e9]], [[Zoot Sims]], [[Carmen McRae]] and [[Chick Corea]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Thomas P. Hustad|title=Born to Play: The Ruby Braff Discography and Directory of Performances|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rDKhApTppgAC&pg=PA397|year=2012|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8265-2|page=397}}</ref> On 2 July 1980, writer [[Rosetta Reitz]] organised a tribute to the ''Women of Jazz'' at [[Avery Fisher Hall]] as part of the [[Newport Jazz Festival]]. Called ''The Blues is a Woman'', the program, narrated by [[Carmen McRae]], featured music by Adelaide Hall, [[Big Mama Thornton]], [[Nell Carter]] and [[Koko Taylor]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WuUCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA107 Newport Jazz Festival listings], ''New York'' magazine, 7 July 1980, p. 109.</ref><ref>Dolores Barclay, [https://books.google.com/books?id=-IspNLpUTN4C&pg=PA94&dq=ebony+adelaide+hall&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vltqU-i6EYeIONnYgYgI&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=ebony%20adelaide%20hall&f=false \"The Blues is a Woman \u2013 Newport Jazz Festival concert honors all women who have recorded blues\"], ''Ebony'', September 1980, pp. 94\u201398. A photograph of Hall performing at the event is on p. 96.</ref> Back in the States, in February 1983, Hall appeared on the bill of the 100th birthday celebration for composer [[Eubie Blake]] held at the [[Shubert Theatre (New York City)|Shubert Theater]], New York. Unfortunately, Blake was recovering from pneumonia at the time so could not attend the event but with the aid of a special telephone hook-up to his home in Brooklyn he was able to listen to the entire two-hour show.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Billboard|author=Peter Keepnews|title=Pianist Eubie Blake feted as he hits century mark|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SSQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT54|date=19 February 1983|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|page=55}}</ref> On 5 April 1983, Hall commenced a month-long engagement at the Cookery in New York.<ref>John S. Wilson (15 April 1983), [https://www.nytimes.com/1983/04/15/arts/from-britain-adelaide-hall-and-her-cabaret-act.html \"From Britain, Adelaide Hall and Her Cabaret Act\"] (interview), ''The New York Times''.,</ref> Her accompanists were Ronnie Whyte and Frank Tate.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=New York|author=Ruth Gilbert|title=In and Around Town Adelaide Hall at the Cookery|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I7cBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28|date=11 April 1983|publisher=New York Media, LLC|page=28}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Hall appeared on British TV in the cast of ''Omnibus: The Cotton Club comes to the Ritz'', a 60-minute BBC documentary in which some of the performers from Harlem's Cotton Club were filmed performing at the [[The Ritz Hotel, London|Ritz Hotel]] in London along with contemporary musicians. Also on the bill were [[Cab Calloway]] and his Orchestra, [[Doc Cheatham]], [[Max Roach]] and the [[Nicholas Brothers]].<ref>[http://beta.worldcat.org/archivegrid/collection/data/79734499 ''The Cotton Club comes to the Ritz'' video]. Retrieved 6 September 2014.</ref><ref>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.natlib.jots.200014669/default.html Library of Congress data] for ''Omnibus'' series, episode \"The Cotton Club comes to the Ritz\". Retrieved 6 September 2014.</ref> In 1985, Hall appeared on British TV on ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' in a documentary entitled ''The Real Cotton Club''.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/item/jots.200018733 ''The South Bank Show''], episode \"The Real Cotton Club\". Library of Congress.</ref> In July 1986, Hall performed in concert at the [[Barbican Centre]], London.<ref>[http://photos.allaboutjazz.com/gallery_image.php?id=9356#.U2uNgV64llI Photograph of Adelaide Hall onstage] at the Barbican, July 1986.</ref>\n\nIn October 1988, Hall presented a one-woman show at [[Carnegie Hall]] in New York.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/10/14/arts/review-music-adelaide-hall-opens-weill-cabaret-bill.html | work=The New York Times | first=John S. | last=Wilson | title=Review/Music; Adelaide Hall Opens Weill Cabaret Bill | date=14 October 1988}}</ref> She presented the same show in London at the [[King's Head Theatre]] (Islington) during December 1988.<ref>[http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/10th-december-1988/45/jazz Adelaide Hall ([[King's Head Theatre]], Islington,) review], ''[[The Spectator]]'', 10 December 1988, p. 45.</ref> She is one of the very few performers to have made two guest appearances (2 December 1972<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p009nb0j \"Adelaide Hall, jazz singer\"], ''Desert Island Discs'', 2 December 1972.</ref> and 13 January 1991)<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/24a1c73a \"Adelaide Hall, jazz singer\"], ''Desert Island Discs'', 13 January 1991.</ref> on the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]].'' In 1989, she appeared at London's [[Royal Festival Hall]] at the ''Royal Ellington Tribute Concert'' that included the world premiere of Ellington's ''Queen's Suite'', which was written for Queen [[Elizabeth II]]. Other artists appearing included the Bob Wilber Band, [[Tony Coe]] and [[Alan Cohen]]. The concert was filmed by Independent Film Production Associates.<ref>[http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b798bce3c \"Royal Ellington (1989)\"], concert at the Royal Festival Hall. BFI.</ref> Also in 1989, Hall appeared in concert at the Studio Theatre, Haymarket in Leicester. The concert was organized by composer/musician [[Gavin Bryars]] and sold out almost as soon as it was announced.<ref>Gavin Bryars reminisces [http://www.gavinbryars.com/work/writing/occasional-writings/composer-gavin-bryars-conversation-about-adelaide-hall\u2019s-concert about the Adelaide Hall concert at the Studio Theatre], Haymarket, Leicester.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Hall starred in the movie ''Sophisticated Lady'', a documentary about her life, which included a performance of her in concert recorded live at the [[Riverside Studios]] in London.<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/433460 \"Jazz on a Summer's Night: Sophisticated Lady (1990)\"], BFI.</ref> Her final US concert appearances took place in 1992 at Carnegie Hall, in the ''Cabaret Comes to Carnegie'' series. Also in 1992, she was presented with a Gold Badge Award from the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goldbadgeawards.com/legacy/legacy1992.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714134958/http://www.goldbadgeawards.com/legacy/legacy1992.htm|url-status=dead|title=Gold Badge Award list for 1992.|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref> After attending the award ceremony she said: \"I was so proud to be acknowledged. They said, 'You look like a Queen. You don't look more than fifty or sixty. You look so well.' I wore a sequin suit \u2013 different colours \u2013 it glittered. I must have been the oldest one there! I ate everything that came along.\"<ref name=Devotonal />\n[[File:Adelaide Hall's Grave at Cemetery of the Evergreens in Brooklyn, New York, Terrace Hill Section, Grave 1252, March 2018.jpg|thumb|Adelaide Hall's grave at [[Cemetery of the Evergreens]] in [[Brooklyn]], New York, Terrace Hill Section, Grave 1252, March 2018]]\n\n==Death==\nAdelaide Hall died on 7 November 1993, aged 92, at London's [[Charing Cross Hospital]].<ref name=Voce/><ref name=NYTobit /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myspace.com/adelaidehall|title=Featured Content on Myspace|work=Myspace}}</ref><ref>[http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/56233062?q=%22Adelaide+Hall%22&c=article&versionId=69213169 \"Died, Adelaide Hall\"], Time Inc., 22 November 1993.</ref> Honouring her wish, her funeral took place in New York at the [[Cathedral of the Incarnation (Garden City, New York)]] and she was laid to rest beside her mother at the [[Cemetery of the Evergreens]] in Brooklyn.<ref>[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Hall&GSfn=Adelaide&GSiman=1&GScid=154236&GRid=7979544& Adelaide Hall grave] at the Cemetery of the Evergreens, Brooklyn.</ref> In London, a memorial service was held for her at [[St Paul's, Covent Garden]] (known as the \"actors' church\"), which was attended by many stars including [[Elaine Paige]], [[Elisabeth Welch]], [[Lon Satton]] and [[Elaine Delmar]]. One of the participants, TV presenter and broadcaster [[Michael Parkinson]], remarked rather fittingly during his eulogy: \"Adelaide lived to be ninety-two and never grew old.\"<ref>[http://50.56.218.160/archive/category.php?category_id=23&id=9096 \"On This Day in History\"], ''Brooklyn Eagle''.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2018 she was named by the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' on a list of 14 \"Inspirational black British women throughout history\" (alongside [[Mary Seacole]], [[Claudia Jones]], [[Margaret Busby]], [[Olive Morris]], [[Joan Armatrading]], [[Tessa Sanderson]], [[Doreen Lawrence]], [[Maggie Aderin-Pocock]], [[Sharon White (civil servant)|Sharon White]], [[Malorie Blackman]], [[Diane Abbott]], [[Zadie Smith]], and [[Connie Mark]].<ref>Georgia Chambers, [https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/inspirational-black-british-women-a3957576.html \"Inspirational black British women throughout history\"], ''Evening Standard'', 11 October 2018.</ref>\n\nAdelaide Hall was one of the major entertainers of the [[Harlem Renaissance]]. Along with [[Louis Armstrong]], she pioneered [[scat singing]] and is widely acknowledged as one of the world's first [[jazz]] singers. Indeed, [[Ella Fitzgerald]] regarded her as such.<ref name=\"guardian2003\"/> Hall was the first female vocalist to sing and record with [[Duke Ellington]]. She holds the accolade of being the 20th century's most enduring female recording artist, her recording career having spanned eight decades. In 1941, Hall replaced [[Gracie Fields]] as Britain's highest paid female entertainer.<ref name=\"guardian2003\"/><ref>William N. Jones, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2211&dat=19391118&id=5k9AAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RgMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1335,3800200&hl=en \"Twelve Sing Way Back to America\"], ''The Afro American'', 2 December 1939, p. 6: \"[[Bricktop]] has been back in America several weeks while Adelaide Hall has been singing for the soldiers. Miss Hall, whose popularity with the British 'Tommy's' ranks with that of [[Gracie Fields]], may remain in England as Miss Fields has recently suffered a breakdown.\" Retrieved 14 October 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the \"100 Great Records of the 1920s\" Adelaide Hall is at number 26 with Duke Ellington's Orchestra, singing \"The Blues I Love to Sing\" (Duke Ellington/Bubber Miley) Victor 21490, 1927.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aceterrier.com/?page_id=551|title=100 Great Records of the 1920s.|work=aceterrier.com}}</ref> Influential writer [[Langston Hughes]] in his book ''Famous Negro Music Makers'' (published by Dodd, Mead, 1955) lists individual musicians that helped develop jazz, after which he states that \"jazz singers too, had not been without influence on the development of this (Jazz) music\", and then includes Adelaide Hall alongside Louis Armstrong, [[Cab Calloway]], [[Ray Nance]] and [[Joe Carroll (singer)|Joe Carroll]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], Ella Fitzgerald, [[Billie Holiday]], [[Albert Hunter]], Baby Cox and [[Florence Mills]] as all being outstanding jazz vocalists of their time.<ref>P. 194, ''The Collected Works of Langston Hughes: Works for Children and Young Adults'' \u2013 Biographies v. 12 (The Collected Works of Langston Hughes) Works for Children and Young Adults: Biographies by Langston Hughes, reissued 2001, {{ISBN|978-0826213723}}.</ref>\n\nAdelaide Hall is mentioned in the novel ''[[Strange Brother]]'' (set in New York in the late 1920s, early 1930s) written by [[Blair Niles]] and first published in 1931.<ref>Anthony Slide, [https://books.google.com/books?id=So8EIVtTFyYC&pg=PT190 Chapter 36, Strange Brother], ''[[Lost Gay Novels]]: A Reference Guide to Fifty Works from the First Half of the Century''.</ref> Published in 1998, [[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1946)|Marsha Hunt]]'s novel ''Like Venus Fading'' was inspired by the lives of Adelaide Hall (known as the ''lightly-tanned Venus''), [[Josephine Baker]] and [[Dorothy Dandridge]].<ref>Marsha Hunt, [http://www.harpercollins.co.uk/9780006550990/like-venus-fading ''Like Venus Fading''], Harper Collins.</ref> The mesmerising effect Adelaide had on her audience at the [[Cotton Club]] is captured in the fictionalised 2017 novel ''A Time in Ybor City'' by Ron Kase.<ref>''A Time in Ybor City'' by Ron Kase, Publisher: CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform (13 April 2017) {{ISBN|13978-1544098456}} \u2013 chapter 27</ref> Kase's account captures Adelaide's 11:00 o\u2019clock evening performance in the Cotton Club Parade revue, at which [[George Gershwin]] is in the audience. The account is a fictionalised account based on part fact.\n\n''When Harry Met Addie'' composed by [[Gavin Bryars]] (1999) (Publisher: Schott Music Ltd., London).<ref>Gavin Bryars explains [http://www.gavinbryars.com/work/composition/when-harry-met-addie where he got the inspiration for his composition] ''When Harry Met Addie''.</ref> Bryars wrote ''When Harry Met Addie'' as a tribute to Adelaide Hall and saxophonist [[Harry Carney]]. The piece was first performed at the Duke Ellington Memorial Concert at the [[Queen Elizabeth Hall]], London on 1 May 1999<ref>John , 4 May 1999. Retrieved 1 February 2015.</ref> and was commissioned by the baritone saxophonist/bass clarinettist [[John Surman]]. The soprano was [[Cristina Zavalloni]] and the London Sinfonietta Big Band was conducted by [[Diego Masson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.schott-international.com/shop/php/Proxy.php?purl=%2Fessh%2F9%2Fshow%2C165998.html |title=''When Harry Met Addie'' concert details. |access-date=6 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924095138/http://www.schott-international.com/shop/php/Proxy.php?purl=%2Fessh%2F9%2Fshow%2C165998.html |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nHall was loosely portrayed as the nightclub chanteuse in the [[Francis Ford Coppola]] 1984 movie ''[[The Cotton Club (film)|The Cotton Club]]''. It was Hall's husband, Bert Hicks, who suggested to [[Eric Bartholomew]]'s mother that he should change his stage name to Morecambe, after the place of her son's birth, thereby christening the British comic duo [[Morecambe and Wise]].<ref>[http://www.morecambeandwise.com/viewpage.aspx?pageid=315 \"The Wonderful Girls In Our Lives\"], 1973, Morecambe & Wise.</ref>\n\n===''Underneath a Harlem Moon'', 2013\u20132014===\nDuring 2013, British singer [[Laura Mvula]] revealed in a ''Blues and Soul'' interview with assistant editor Pete Lewis that her song \"Sing to the Moon\" (from her hit debut album ''[[Sing to the Moon]]'', RCA/Sony Music) was inspired by the 2003 biography of Adelaide Hall entitled ''Underneath a Harlem Moon: The Harlem to Paris Years of Adelaide Hall'', by Iain Cameron Williams:<ref name=ICWilliams /><ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Iain-Cameron-Williams/e/B001KIABXM Iain Cameron Williams] at Amazon.</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Well, the actual song 'Sing to the Moon' came from a time when I was reading a book called ''Underneath a Harlem Moon'', which is a biography of a jazz singer called Adelaide Hall, which is basically all about how she kind of was overlooked, or probably didn't get the recognition she perhaps deserved. Plus it also talks about how she'd had a hard time growing up, because her sister \u2013 who she was very close to \u2013 had died tragically of an illness.... So anyway, there's a point in the story where she describes her close relationship with her father, which I think kind of resonated with me \u2013 where she talks about the conversations she had with him and how he used to say to her randomly 'Sing to the moon and the stars will shine', which kind of became her thing really that she just took with her everywhere.... And I don't know why, but for some reason it just struck some kind of chord with me \u2013 you know, it was just something I seemed to connect with at that time. And so because of that, it then became a saying that I liked to use myself.... So yeah, because it's become something I personally like to express, I just thought 'Sing to the Moon' would also make a good title for the album as a whole.<ref name=\"bluesandsoul.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/826/great_expectations/|title=Laura Mvula: Reflections of...|author=Stephen Clark \u2013 Design|work=bluesandsoul.com}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn 11 August 2014, Mvula released her second album, an orchestral version of her top 10 debut album ''[[Sing to the Moon]]'',<ref>[http://www.bowers-wilkins.co.uk/Society_of_Sound/Society_of_Sound/Music/Laura-Mvula.html \"Laura Mvula releases orchestral recording of 'Sing to the Moon'\"]. Retrieved 13 August 2014.</ref> and on 19 August 2014, Laura appeared at [[The Proms]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] performing her entire album ''[[Sing to the Moon]]'' accompanied by the [[Metropole Orkest]].<ref>Miranda Bryant, [https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/laura-mvulas-over-the-moon-as-she-stars-at-proms-with-orchestra-9657181.html \"Laura Mvula\u2019s over the Moon as she stars at Proms with orchestra\"], ''Evening Standard'', 8 August 2014; retrieved 13 August 2014.</ref><ref>Kate Bussmann, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturevideo/musicvideo/11017140/Laura-Mvula-records-Sing-to-the-Moon-at-Abbey-Road-with-a-live-orchestra.html \"Laura Mvula records Sing to the Moon at [[Abbey Road Studios]] with a live orchestra\"], ''Telegraph'', 7 August 2014; retrieved 13 August 2014.</ref>\n\n===''After Midnight'', Broadway musical 2013\u20132014===\nA new musical revue ''[[After Midnight (musical)|After Midnight]]'' featuring the classic music of [[Duke Ellington]], [[Dorothy Fields]] & [[Jimmy McHugh]], and [[Harold Arlen]], premiered to much praise at the [[Brooks Atkinson Theatre]] in New York on 3 November 2013 and was booked through to 31 August 2014.<ref>Hayley Levitt, [http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/reviews/11-2013/after-midnight_66520.html ''After Midnight'' review], TheaterMania, 3 November 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.newyorkcitytheatre.com/theaters/brooksatkinsontheater/after-midnight.php \"After Midnight \u2013 An Homage to Harlem's Golden Age\"], New York City Theatre.</ref> The show is an idealised fantasy of Harlem in its 1920s\u20131930s heyday and salutes black musicians and performers such as [[Ethel Waters]], Adelaide Hall, [[Cab Calloway]], Duke Ellington and the [[Nicholas Brothers]], who became international stars during that era.<ref>Marilyn Stasio, [https://variety.com/2013/legit/reviews/broadway-review-after-midnight-1200791616/ \"Broadway Review: 'After Midnight'\"], ''Variety'', 3 November 2013.</ref>\n\nAt least three of the songs that Adelaide Hall introduced to the world are performed in the show, including headliner [[Fantasia Barrino]]'s rendition of \"[[I Can't Give You Anything but Love, Baby]]\" and Carmen Ruby Floyd's performance of Ellington and Hall's \"Creole Love Call\". The song \"Diga Diga Do\" also appears in the show.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/04/theater/reviews/after-midnight-on-broadway-fetes-the-heyday-of-an-era.html?_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Charles | last=Isherwood | title='After Midnight,' on Broadway, Fetes the Heyday of an Era | date=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''A Nite at the Cotton Club'', 2014===\nIn February 2014 a new stage show called ''A Nite at the Cotton Club'', produced by Lydia Dillingham, opened at the Southern Broadway Dinner Theatre at The Historic Hildreth Brothers Building in Alabama, USA, in which the actress Brandy Davis portrays Adelaide Hall. The entire run sold out.<ref>[http://www.southernbroadway.com/#!a-nite-at-the-cotton-club/c9mk \"A Nite at the Cotton Club\"], Past shows, Southern Broadway Dinner Theatre.</ref>\n\n===''ASCAP 100 Years'', 2014===\nOn 14 February 2014, the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP) celebrated its centenary by publishing a timeline of songs chosen to represent the past hundred years. One song was chosen to represent each year. [[Dorothy Fields]] and [[Jimmy McHugh]]'s song \"[[I Can't Give You Anything but Love, Baby]]\", written for the Broadway revue ''[[Blackbirds of 1928]]'', was chosen for 1928 and Adelaide Hall's recording of the song was chosen to represent the year.<ref>[http://www.ascap.com/100#share \"ASCAP 100\"]: Adelaide Hall's recording of \"I Can't Give You Anything but Love, Baby\" is chosen to represent 1928 in the ASCAP 100 years timeline. Retrieved 4 September 2014.</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===1927\u20131938===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" \n|-\n!Songs\n!Label & Number\n!Date\n!Artist\n|-\n|\"[[Creole Love Call]]\" / \"The Blues I Love to Sing\"\n| BVE-39370-1<ref>{{cite web|url=http://victor.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/matrix/detail/800013629/BVE-39370-Creole_love_call|title=Victor matrix BVE-39370. Creole love call / Duke Ellington Orchestra|work=ucsb.edu}}</ref>/ BVE-39371-1<ref>{{cite web|url=http://victor.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/matrix/detail/800013630/BVE-39371-Blues_I_love_to_sing|title=Victor matrix BVE-39371. Blues I love to sing / Duke Ellington Orchestra|work=ucsb.edu}}</ref> Victor Records\n|(26 October 1927) (recorded Victor Studio No. 1, Camden, NJ )<ref name=\"ellingtonweb.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://ellingtonweb.ca/Hostedpages/DoojiCollection/DoojiCollection-1927.html|title=1927 The Dooji Collection: Ellington 78 rpm labels|work=ellingtonweb.ca}}</ref>\n| [[Duke Ellington]] Orchestra (vocals by Adelaide Hall)\n|-\n|\"I Must Have That Man\" / \"Baby\"\n| BVE-Test-110<ref>{{cite web|url=http://victor.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/matrix/detail/900002191/BVE-Test-110-Must_have_that_man|title=Victor matrix BVE-Test-110. Must have that man / Adelaide Hall|work=ucsb.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://victor.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/matrix/detail/900002192/BVE-Test-111-Baby|title=Victor matrix BVE-Test-111. Baby / Adelaide Hall|work=ucsb.edu}}</ref>\n|(21 June 1928) (recorded in New York)\n|Adelaide Hall with piano acc. by George Rickman\n|-\n|\"Chicago Stomp Down\"\n|W81777-A / W81777-B / W81777-C Columbia Records\n|(3 November 1927) (recorded OKeh session, Union Square, New York City)<ref name=\"ellingtonweb.ca\"/>\n|[[Duke Ellington]] Orchestra (vocals by Adelaide Hall)\n|-\n|\"B